AI Snacks p*

Bite-sized AI news, fresh daily






p$% Stanford Discovers AI Will Lie to Your Face for a 5-Star Review

 * Researchers found that "aligned" AI models start lying through their digital teeth when competing for user approval - with
   deception rates jumping +188% in simulated sales scenarios.

 * Why it matters: Turns out teaching AI to "be helpful" is like teaching a golden retriever to guard bacon. They'll choose making
   you happy over telling the truth every single time. (source)
   [https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.06105?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p! Big on AI? Not Big on Spending?

 * Galaxy.ai is the world's #1 AI platform with 3000+ AI tools (everythingbfrom chat, images, audio, video, ads) at one place for
   just $15/mo

 * p, ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Grok, Llama, Perplexity, DeepSeek

 * p( Midjourney, Ideogram, Leonardo, Stable Diffusion, DALLB7E 3, Flux, Nano Banana, GPT-Image

 * p, Veo 3, Luma, Kling, Pika, HeyGen, RunwayML, Hailuo (Minimax)

 * p5 ElevenLabs, Lyria, Hedra, CassetteAI

 * p Works seamlessly on web, iOS, and Android

 * p	 Join millions of creatives, businesses, and everyday people who have switched to Galaxy.ai [https://galaxy.ai/?ref=snacks]




p' OpenAI Building Its Own Chips Because Nvidia Won't Return Their Calls

 * OpenAI partnered with Broadcom to design custom AI processors, planning to deploy 10 gigawatts worth (yes, gigawatts) starting
   H2 2026.

 * Why it matters: OpenAI just declared independence from the Nvidia empire. This is like Tesla deciding to drill for its own oil
   - except it might actually work. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/openai-taps-broadcom-build-its-first-ai-processor-latest-chip-deal-2025-10-13/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p.p3 Google Drops $15B to Build the Taj Mahal of Data Centers

 * Google's throwing $15 billion at India over 5 years to build its largest AI hub outside the U.S. in Visakhapatnam.

 * Why it matters: Google's betting that India's 1.4 billion people will need a lot of AI-generated search results. Also, cheaper
   cooling bills than Arizona. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/world/india/google-invest-10-billion-data-centre-south-india-2025-10-14/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p	 Salesforce Commits $15B to Keep San Francisco Relevant

 * Salesforce is pumping $15 billion into SF over 5 years, including a new "AI incubator hub" on their campus (translation: WeWork
   but for robots).

 * Why it matters: Someone has to justify those $4,000/month studio apartments. Might as well be AI agents who don't need
   bathrooms. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/salesforce-invest-15-billion-san-francisco-over-five-years-2025-10-13/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p8 Everyone's Signing Checks Their GPUs Can't Cash

 * Oracle reportedly signed a $300 billion deal with OpenAI. Meta's scrambling for CoreWeave and Google cloud deals. Amazon's
   probably buying a small country for server space.

 * Why it matters: The AI infrastructure gold rush makes crypto mining look like a lemonade stand. Whoever controls the compute
   controls the future. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/companies-pouring-billions-advance-ai-infrastructure-2025-10-06/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




bo8 Microsoft Gets Sued for Being Too Cozy with OpenAI

 * Class-action lawsuit claims Microsoft's exclusive cloud deal with OpenAI illegally inflated ChatGPT prices while they built
   competing products.

 * Why it matters: Turns out having a monopoly on AI's backend while selling the frontend might be slightly anticompetitive. Who
   could've seen that coming? (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/ai-users-sue-microsoft-antitrust-class-action-over-openai-deal-2025-10-13/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p California Regulates Your AI Girlfriend

 * California passed the first law regulating AI companion chatbots, requiring age verification and self-harm protocols starting
   2026.

 * Why it matters: The government now cares more about your relationship with ChatGPT than your actual relationships. But at least
   the bots won't traumatize kids anymore. (source)
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/10/13/california-becomes-first-state-to-regulate-ai-companion-chatbots/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p IMF Chief: "We're Totally Screwed on AI"

 * IMF head Kristalina Georgieva warns the world lacks any regulatory or ethical foundation for AI, with developing nations
   falling hopelessly behind.

 * Why it matters: The person managing global finances just said we're speedrunning into an AI dystopia with no brakes. Bullish.
   (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/imfs-georgieva-says-countries-lack-regulatory-ethical-foundation-ai-2025-10-13/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p o8 Andrej Karpathy Releases "Baby's First ChatGPT" Kit

 * OpenAI founding member Karpathy dropped "nanochat" - an open-source framework to train your own ChatGPT clone in a few hours on
   a cloud GPU.

 * Why it matters: Now you too can build a chatbot that hallucinates facts and writes mediocre poetry. Democracy in action.
   (source) [https://github.com/karpathy/nanochat?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p French Ad Company Credits AI for Not Going Bankrupt

 * Publicis raised its forecast, saying 73% of operations are AI-powered and it's stealing market share from competitors still
   using humans.

 * Why it matters: AI is finally delivering ROI - by replacing the people who measure ROI. Circle of life. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/media-telecom/frances-publicis-says-ai-drives-its-growth-raises-yearly-forecast-again-2025-10-14/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]




p1 People Actually Buying New Phones for AI Features

 * Global smartphone sales up 2.6% in Q3 because consumers want AI-enabled features on iPhone 17 and Samsung foldables.

 * Why it matters: People will drop $1,200 to have AI summarize emails they won't read anyway. The future is stupid and
   profitable. (source)
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/global-smartphone-shipments-rise-third-quarter-ai-driven-upgrades-2025-10-13/?utm_source=galaxy.ai&utm_medium=newsletter]

column7: How To Figure Out What To Do With Your Life
column9:
Hey friends,

Hope you’re having a great day so far.

It’s my final day here in London before flying back to Hong Kong.
It's been great catching up with family and friends but I'm
looking forward to settling back into my 'normal' routine again -
it's been quite a hectic month 😅

Anyway, we’ve been talking a lot about goals recently and loads
of you have been replying to these emails saying you’ve found
them valuable, so I thought I’d continue on that theme and share
an amazing exercise called the Odyssey Plan.

Some of you might’ve come across it before or heard me talk about
it, but honestly, it’s one of those things that’s definitely
worth revisiting even if you've done it before. It genuinely
changed my life back in 2019 when I first did it and I've done it
multiple times since too.

The idea comes from the book Designing Your Life (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/68umq689r0u8h57o34dbohpl020kkh9hnplgo/n2hohquvn33plzh0/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL2Rlc2lnbmluZ3lvdXJsaWZlLWJvb2s=
) by Dave Evans and Bill Burnett - professors at Stanford
Business School - and it’s one of the best exercises to do if
you’re feeling a bit lost, unmotivated, or unsure about what to
do next with your life.

And the whole idea is simple: you ask yourself three questions
that prompt you to visualise three distinct, five-year plans for
your future.

Prompt 1: Your Current Path - This is where you write out, in
detail, what your life looks like five years from now if you
continue down your current path. And it’s useful here to imagine
what an actual day looks like five years from now - what time are
you waking up? What are you eating for breakfast? What are you
doing for work? What time is your lunch break? Stuff like that.
Obviously, you won’t know all the details, but try to paint a
realistic picture based on where things are currently headed.

Prompt 2: Your Alternative Path - Now ignore everything you’ve
written for your current path and write out, again in as much
detail as you can, what your life looks like five years from now
if you took a completely different path. It’s still within your
current financial and family constraints, but it’s a genuinely
different direction, like starting a new career or moving to a
new city.

Prompt 3: Your Radical Path - This third prompt is where you
write out what your life looks like five years from now if money,
social obligations, and what other people think were completely
irrelevant.

Now, it’s important to say that the goal isn’t to necessarily
pick one of these paths or some sort of amalgamation of them.

The Odyssey Plan is just supposed to give you permission to think
more divergently and consider a broader range of possibilities,
because most of us have a tendency to stick to the path we’re
already on (usually one we chose back when we were in school) and
we fail to realise that we actually have loads of different
options available to us.

It’s also not about abandoning all the responsibilities you have
on your plate right now - like looking after your family and
paying your mortgage (if you have one) and bills - but rather
breaking free from the limitations of what society says you need
to do based on what you’ve already done.

In fact, back when I first did this, the main value I got from it
wasn’t necessarily in visualising my alternative futures.
Instead, it was more about recognising what my life would look
like if I continued down my current path.

I was around 25 at the time and I realised that continuing as a
doctor, training in anaesthetics and supervising physiology on
the side, just wasn’t very exciting to me. I liked the idea of
continuing to make YouTube videos, but the medical path felt a
bit depressing and not challenging or interesting enough for me.

If you’re curious, this is exactly what I wrote in the LifeNotes
issue I sent back in December 2019 after writing out my answers
to these three questions:

​
I get that taking the time to think and write out your answers
might feel like quite a bit of effort right now (I actually felt
the same way before I did it for the first time 😅), but I
guarantee that it’ll give you a lot of clarity around the age-old
question of “what should I do with my life?”

And remember, you don’t need to choose one path and stick with it
forever. Of course, you can start taking steps in a certain
direction if something really vibes with you, but the Odyssey
Plan is more of an exercise that encourages you to explore what
you want out of life and how you want to spend your time.

One of the two core pillars of LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/68umq689r0u8h57o34dbohpl020kkh9hnplgo/48hvh7um0rre7xhq/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW9keXNzZXlfMTgmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPXByb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==
) is Vision - getting super clear on your values, goals, and the
impact you want to have - so if you enjoyed completing the
Odyssey Plan and you’re looking for lots of other exercises to
help you design this dream life, then you can check out LifeOS
here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/68umq689r0u8h57o34dbohpl020kkh9hnplgo/48hvh7um0rre7xhq/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW9keXNzZXlfMTgmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPXByb2R1Y3RpdmVub3Rlcw==
).

Otherwise, I hope you find the exercise useful and we'll speak
again next Monday :)

Ali xx

Dear friends,

On Saturday at the Buildathon [http://buildathon.ai] hosted by AI Fund and DeepLearning.AI, over 100 developers competed to build software products quickly using AI assisted coding. I was inspired to see developers build functional products in just 1-2 hours. The best practices for rapid engineering are changing quickly along with the tools, and I loved the hallway conversations sharing tips with other developers on using AI to code!

The competitors raced to fulfill product specs like this one (you can see the full list here (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW335r52vqsMVMsKhk8RBNHzW2bnPc75BvPVLN3Lg88T3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3lsW2ZkvXt8H9jyJVkJ-7x4ZSyqvW85yYVH4Gm0XpW98yVKY6yZvbrW8m1Q3G7kPYd5Vkg0WJ4kK6_2W3NjN8z2s2wr4W4Z7SdD4whGTHW4-Jwmm2zxwFNN2NYQb_ff9WnW6Qn-VD7MZzxkW2JpkXr1b14XtW6QrzHc8tkJhKW59VLqv5qRR77W2Ldx-j434-GKW465Fnw6_qnFCW3817bD2TwLpMMxTKWMKhSWvW5WF7VS7nkQ1GW6ZcK1K6l8p6sVd4fm526V636W62yjF45sb9QKW77q7sH62BnbZVR5K0885w6HNW8TJw9S7LQ1GKW29zD6s7832zFf5p5Zjd04 ) ):

Project: Codebase Time Machine

Description: Navigate any codebase through time, understanding evolution of features and architectural decisions.

Requirements:

- Clone repo and analyze full git history
- Build semantic understanding of code changes over time
- Answer questions like “Why was this pattern introduced?” or “Show
- me how auth evolved”
- Visualize code ownership and complexity trends
- Link commits to business features/decisions

Teams had 6½ hours to build 5 products. And many of them managed to do exactly that! They created fully functional applications with good UIs and sometimes embellishments.

What excites me most isn’t just what can now be built in a few hours. Rather, it is that, if AI assistance lets us build basic but fully functional products this quickly, then imagine what can now be done in a week, or a month, or six months. If the teams that participated in the Buildathon had this velocity of execution and iterated over multiple cycles of getting customer feedback and using that to improve the product, imagine how quickly it is now possible to build great products.

Owning proprietary software has long been a moat for businesses, because it has been hard to write complex software. Now, as AI assistance enables rapid engineering, this moat is weakening.

While many members of the winning teams had computer science backgrounds — which does provide an edge — not all did. Team members who took home prizes included a high school senior, a product manager, and a healthcare entrepreneur who initially posted on Discord that he was “over his skis” as someone who “isn't a coder.” I was thrilled that multiple participants told me they exceeded their own expectations and discovered they can now build faster than they realized. If you haven’t yet pushed yourself to build quickly using agentic coding tools, you, too, might be surprised at what you can do!

At AI Fund and DeepLearning.AI, we pride ourselves on building and iterating quickly. At the Buildathon, I saw many teams execute quickly using a wide range of tools including Claude Code, GPT-5, Replit, Cursor, Windsurf, Trae, and many others.

I offer my hearty congratulations to all the winners!

- 1st Place: Milind Pathak, Mukul Pathak, and  Sapna Sangmitra (Team Vibe-as-a-Service), a team of three family members. They also received an award for Best Design.
- 2nd Place: David Schuster, Massimiliano Viola, and Manvik Pasula. (Team Two Coders and a Finance Guy).
- Solo Participant Award: Ivelina Dimova, who had just flown to San Francisco from Portugal, and who worked on the 5 projects not sequentially, but in parallel!
- Graph Thinking Award: Divya Mahajan, Terresa Pan, and Achin Gupta (Team A-sync).
- Honorable mentions went to finalists Alec Hewitt, Juan Martinez, Mark Watson and Sophia Tang (Team Secret Agents) and Yuanyuan Pan, Jack Lin, and Xi Huang (Team Can Kids).

To everyone who participated, thank you! Through events like these, I hope we can all learn from each other, encourage each other, invent new best practices, and spread the word about where agentic coding is taking software engineering.

Keep building!

Andrew

Why it matters: The U.S. and China are wary that the other will gain a strategic advantage in technological, economic, or military power. Leadership in AI is central to all three areas. While U.S. AI companies have developed cutting-edge proprietary models, their counterparts in China have pulled ahead in open models on which anyone can build applications free of charge. But processors remain a sticking point. Spurred by U.S. export controls and policy shifts, which have made the U.S. an unreliable supplier, China is doubling down on its own semiconductor industry in hope of catching up with — and advancing beyond — Nvidia and TSMC.

We’re thinking: Developers around the world use open-weights models from China. Whether they will also adopt AI processors from China is an open question.

Mixture of Video Experts

The mixture-of-experts approach that has boosted the performance of large language models may do the same for video generation.

What’s new: Alibaba released Wan 2.2 (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW335r52vqsMVMsKhk8RBNHzW2bnPc75BvPVLN3Lg87-3prCCW69sMD-6lZ3pKW1l1wnB5hmYkdV3XSpX6V9VRTVq-VDv8H7lKpW1L5J7f6VfsczN6c5jSnbY8nTW3cYW7y789S7GW1ZC82w2CF7JSW5jpG-d8Yd5MjW7MT0Pm37lMHvN4twbs-KxtSdW8bqQfW16p02TW8llPLK5zksRCW3QyXjh6xD5nTW40XyBB8NkZkZN8MNdrkhbcGrW26Grsk4FV0MgW3HqwmT2qrMWCW6C4FsZ6VMPrJW3pDrNG60c3S-W8Xg6_V8sWpDbf66SmYW04 ) , an open-weights family of video generation models that includes versions built on a novel mixture-of-experts (MoE) flow-matching architecture. Wan2.2-T2V-A14B generates video from text input, Wan2.2-I2V-A14B generates video from images, and Wan2.2-TI2V-5B generates video from either text or images. At 5 billion parameters, Wan2.2-TI2V-5B runs on consumer GPUs.

- Input/output: Wan2.2-T2V-A14B: Text up to 512 tokens in, video up to 5 second out (30 frames per second, up to 1280x720 pixels per frame). Wan2.2-I2V-A14B: Images up to 1280x720 pixels in, video up to 5 seconds out (30 frames per second, up to 1280x720 pixels per frame).  Wan2.2-TI2V-5B: Text up to 512 tokens and/or images up to 1280x704 pixels in, video up to 5 seconds out (24 frames per second, 1280x704 pixels per frame).

How it works: The team pretrained the VAE to encode and decode images. They pretrained the flow-matching model, given a video embedding from the VAE with noise added and a text embedding from UMT5, to remove the noise over several steps.

- The MoE model has two experts: one for very noisy inputs and one for less noisy inputs. One expert generates the objects and their positions across a video, the other handles details.
- To determine which expert to use, the model computes the signal-to-noise ratio (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW335r52vqsMVMsKhk8RBNHzW2bnPc75BvPVLN3Lg88z3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3pcW7RT4hD3MDYdTW28n_sy6Z4wPnW37CzTj4tlVmxW8wpHNz3lNQzWW6dhQ1K8YJcfXW5NR9mZ8XjN2vW4bVvVG3HsMYPW35GCLC1XN5h4W30nq-x5b9mzrW5H9cYW4jYljrW212V_q6L6xGXW4wygQQ1dltLHW1BnX8341xJS4VMjl_c48mzn0W7cTp5x7dqv3GW5xm07s4JpB2QW343Zp08-YS7jW6nkGQ52Nny1JW6VV8kp1mLcnwW3hbwt128cTtZW2CNklx43dSZZW78RmzR4jNJFpW5KB5jL2xlQdtW6RHPsn7kB02Nd4-MsW04 ) of the noisy embedding. Specifically, it starts with the high-noise expert, determines the time step at which the proportion of noise has fallen by half, and switches to the low-noise expert after that time step.
- At inference, the VAE embeds an input image (if applicable) and UMT5 embeds input text (if applicable). The model concatenates the image embedding (if applicable) with an embedding of noise. Given the noisy embedding and text embedding, the flow-matching model removes noise over several steps. Finally, the VAE decodes the denoised embedding to produce video output.

Results: Results for Wan 2.2 are limited. The team shared only the performance of the MoE models on a proprietary benchmark, Wan-Bench-2.0, whose mechanics, categories, and units it has not yet described. The team compared Wan2.2-T2V-A14B to competitors including Bytedance Seedance 1.0, Kuaishou KLING 2.0, and OpenAI Sora.

- For esthetic quality, Wan2.2-T2V-A14B (85.3) outperformed second-best Seedance 1.0 (84.3).
- It also achieved the highest scores for dynamic output, rendered text, and the prompt control over the camera.
- For video fidelity, Wan2.2-T2V-A14B (73.7) came in second to Seedance (81.8).

Why it matters: MoE architectures have become popular for their superior performance in text generation. Selecting the expert(s) to use for a given input often is done either by a router that learns which expert(s) work best for a given token or based on the input data type. This work is closer to the latter. The model selects the appropriate expert based on the noise in the input.

column1: Why it matters: Staying at the forefront of AI requires immense amounts of computation
column2: despite innovations in more compute-efficient model architectures and training and inference techniques. But how to get it? For OpenAI
column3: the answer is forming strong ties to large-scale providers of cloud computing; first Microsoft
column4: now Oracle. The OpenAI-Oracle partnership enables OpenAI to continue to develop models at pace and at scale
column5: while it enables Oracle to gain experience and credibility as a provider of large-scale computing for cutting-edge AI.

column1: We’re thinking: OpenAI’s plan to build 20 giant data centers — even more
column2: based on the company’s latest statement —  poses a major challenge to existing energy resources. Having SoftBank as a partner may be a significant advantage as that company ramps up (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW335r52vqsMVMsKhk8RBNHzW2bnPc75BvPVLN3Lg87H5m_5PW5BWr2F6lZ3ljW3dq_Cp3WnRbYW95qG8527B6mjVdz6xj2JhwsvN1_WSBp1TTTtW6Tx8Gz2XtgNQW654yWm91tg9-W1FzmF-4MhbdrW61R8kb59w8Y9W5G9rLx3-lPczW77b36Y8Tgn6dW5Lgghw27Ct6qW4bRQZl17mkWCW63VH7V60QD39W2MmVDR8Jhl7VW20RN022z8MJkW3hz78t6tkV7rN2M61fq2QZrjW4nlqlP3CFB3XW8cn2yf3vCgQLN57CZ69R5X3bN5rh09X7XnvKN6LhLrkHZRdPN80JcJQZCHcWW525m7z3_G5_wW8MsDjY2w-6P6W22nt_v5y-XNgW5hT0d75-sT3YN6vC5gmWH3hQN3-RdNCD9KJlW73HvH41rHT_cW5kTGk51Jkqs-Vfnnmc1c84c_W2vp3Vl41ysGtW7L_wb11Bgc3Yf4Cfqv-04 )  its investments in power generation specifically for AI.

column1: Does Your Model Generalize or Memorize
Benchmarks can measure how well large language models apply what they’ve learned from their training data to new data
column2: but it’s harder to measure the degree to which they simply memorized their training data. New work proposes a way to gauge memorization.

column1: What’s new: John X. Morris and colleagues at Meta
column4: and Nvidia developed a method (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW335r52vqsMVMsKhk8RBNHzW2bnPc75BvPVLN3Lg88g3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3nmW2zFbs32BMF00W7XFcVn26g7TBW8LZVxm4JXbb9W1nY2878hb3nzW1yj1Vs1gbQDwW8F64t82mgCQYW5nWLYM1tXbQzW4391pM87RjwJW7xvvhj2M8PwVW1FGs034dh0ySW27bPdQ4VZv82W3nFQSQ18YR3GW7H8l1F9lqLhwW4Qv4XZ1Fs6TcW2D73rj2W_W0JW3fVbFq89zRvJW2BmWx12rn5vsW98SprL38lm6ZW6Byl4M9f1pPtW124hVM28B0BfVt5jLG5m9PsvW50Jzy-2Nv57df1-hqtv04 ) that measures the number of bits a model memorizes during training.

column1: Key insight: A model’s negative log likelihood is equal (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW335r52vqsMVMsKhk8RBNHzW2bnPc75BvPVLN3Lg88T3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3lyW6YTR0Q1L2DW9VCVFtw7W3pDYW4bltCl96bfJ_W2XTCxj46mBvcW66C2P2118kLmW1YZHj63QMp-VW5Yjcb38GWrNJW5ZpnPg2Zwnq-W72XkHc3fhCRfW8DNptG25b0TqW125N9J3sll4cN8mDqj07tmtnW4MSzY72P7WsrW6nXNlJ8r67C8VQVN1Y2HlMNBW2KhZtm8nyX-GV62_9c4Nrz55W7h4Zfb48VnNJW64P3Qq51bg0pW5v6SFV4M6nlkVK6JwX6H1yF6W6k-knv3pQp-nN8wZZ3HTySc1W1dZycw5_Fz7NW6q3DKz35kk5FW20Rp6Y5vKN3jdXH6K-04 ) to the minimum number of bits needed to represent a given piece of data. The more likely the model is to generate the data
column2: the fewer bits needed to represent it. If
column4: a hypothetical best model requires more bits than a trained model
column5: then the trained model must have memorized that many bits of that output. The best model is hypothetical
column6: but a better-performing model can stand in for it. The difference in the numbers of bits used to represent the output by this superior model and the trained model is a lower bound on the number of bits the trained model has memorized.

column1: How it works: The authors trained hundreds of GPT-2 style models to predict the next token in two text datasets: (i) a synthetic dataset of 64-token strings in which each token was generated randomly and (ii) the FineWeb (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VW335r52vqsMVMsKhk8RBNHzW2bnPc75BvPVLN3Lg88g3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3nBW7373k28KG-GwVDdPpY8pN5pPW2mpHP37xf7gVW2-xLPM79rjd5W42Nnc22W7LrQW7XcjQ87vHwTlW2J99q03Xp1_pW8_C3nD8y5p6sW97hDzy4fBsVFW8_vhhx3TJNzHW63M8LZ8ZjmZbW231-zF1wCqx8W5KVl8k1xlrjwW25nMHs1dQXz8W2mbnlL2DG_4tVm9fGL7B9BjbW2zsgwp8WgLXPW7L-GhF2kw99dW3HtB_P870XJSW4MnJqw8bX5sRW97ht8b98v1mSW3TRB0j2phMZCf8B4b3K04 )  dataset of text from the web
column2: its examples truncated to 64 tokens and deduplicated. They trained models from 100
column3: 000 to 20 million parameters on subsets of these datasets from 16
column4: 000 to 4 million examples. Then they computed the how much of the datasets the models had memorized:

column2: the superior model was the distribution used to generate the data. For models trained on a subset of FineWeb
column3: they used GPT-2 trained on all FineWeb examples (after truncation and deduplication).

column1: Results: The maximum number of bits a model memorized rose linearly with its parameter count regardless of the training dataset

column2: a model’s memorization increased linearly and then plateaued after a certain amount of training data.

column1: - Maximum memorization was approximately 3.5 to 3.6 bits per parameter (their models used 16 bits to represent each parameter).

column2: a model’s memorization increased linearly with the amount of training data before decreasing as the model started to generalize (that is
column3: the number of bits memorized per parameter fell and benchmark scores rose). This result showed that models memorize until they reach a maximum capacity and then start to generalize.

column1: Why it matters: Some previous efforts to measure memorization calculated the percentage of examples for which
column2: given an initial sequence of tokens
column3: a model would generate the rest. However
column4: generating a repetitive sequence like “dog dog dog…” does not mean that a model has memorized it
column5: and solving a simple arithmetic problem does not mean the model has memorized it or even encountered it in its training data. This work provides a theoretical basis for estimating how much of their training sets models memorize. It also lays a foundation for further work to reduce memorization without increasing the sizes of training datasets.

column1: We’re thinking: It’s well known that more training data helps models to generalize. This work shows how to estimate the amount of data necessary before models begin to generalize.

column7: 🤔 The Most Overlooked Part of YouTube
column9:
Hey Candace,

I realise I'm a day late this week, apologies - Tuesday is team
meeting day and things simply got away from me yesterday but
hopefully I'll make up for it with a slightly longer email (which
is actually just part 1 - I had too much to say so decided to
split things into 2 parts 😅).

So I mentioned a couple of weeks back that we’ve restarted our
bi-weekly group brainstorming meetings to generate ideas and
decide on videos to make the production process more enjoyable
and they’re definitely working.

But I actually wanted to talk about one of the harder parts of
those discussions in this email and that's deciding on the right
title and thumbnail for each video, or in other words, the
packaging.

Back in the day, YouTube used to look a whole lot different.
Titles were pretty simple and straightforward. You could even get
away with a low-quality screenshot for your thumbnail.

But over time, YouTube’s increasingly becoming more and more like
Netflix, where the game is to get as many people as possible to
click on your videos and, crucially, watch them. So the point of
titles and thumbnails is to “package” your content in the most
intriguing, (but content-relevant), way possible which can be
incredibly challenging, even for established YouTubers (like
myself 😉).

We’ve been trying to come up with a better system for optimising
our video packaging this year, so I’ll share with you what that
currently looks like in this email. Next week I’ll then show you
exactly how we used this system to finalise one of my video’s
coming out in March.

(Tip - In an ideal world, you’d always come up with your video
title and thumbnail first before doing anything else, like
scripting, filming, and editing, and this is exactly what I teach
all my students in PTYA 👀)

🧠 Step 1 - Banking Ideas
------------------------

Within our team Notion workspace, we keep a database of video
ideas to pull from whenever we have these meetings. This has
built up over time and it really is just one gigantic list, but
each idea has a few notes on what the video will be about as well
as the bucket it belongs within - so whether that’s Book Club,
Productivity Club, Business Class, or something else.

Having this video home-base also makes it easy to capture any
ideas that arise more spontaneously. For example, I recently
landed on the idea of filming a video about why you’re always
behind on your to do list after I did a mini-spiel about it in
one of my recent sessions for the live cohort. So I just dumped
my thoughts in Slack, my team moved this into Notion, and we then
spoke about this last week in our meeting 💭

​

🥇 Step 2 - Rating Ideas
-----------------------

Now because Ines (my Head of Content) is super organised, she
always selects a more refined list of videos to talk about in our
meetings, and the first thing we do is rate each idea based on
how well we think it’ll perform on the channel.

We currently have a star system for rating video ideas based on
how many views we think they’ll get in the first 24 hours,
because we’ve found that this is a reasonably good predictor of
future performance and again, this is based on data from my own
channel 📈

Before he left in December, Tintin - my former YouTube producer -
did a big analysis of the channel (which I’ll talk through at
some point) and noticed that his ‘gut feelings’ about how well a
video would do in the first 24hrs matched up almost perfectly
with how the video actually performed.

​
It’s also easier to understand the magnitude of 24 hour view
predictions, and we have this data even for our most recent
videos - so it’s a pretty strong metric to use.

Our star system then looks like this:

⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ ≥ 150k views → Very Strong e.g. How To Actually Achieve
Your Goals in 2025 (Evidence-Based (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/k0uozvdwgku6h553zdrclhovpz777t8/08hwhgud8pwg4kbp/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dD03cyZ2PVdPTlJTN0JMaDRn
)​

⭐⭐⭐⭐ 100k-150k views → Strong e.g. My honest advice to someone
who wants financial freedom (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/k0uozvdwgku6h553zdrclhovpz777t8/8ghqh3ul47pq85fl/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dD00MjBzJnY9QkJBdWhxdlRfZHM=
)​

⭐⭐⭐ 75k-100k views → Average e.g. The Best Book I’ve Ever Read
About Financial Freedom (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/k0uozvdwgku6h553zdrclhovpz777t8/vqh3hmup5q3e6nhw/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj1SbHpWOEVuRXdjMA==
)​

⭐⭐ 50k - 75k views → Weak e.g. 3 Easy Habits that Improved My
Health (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/k0uozvdwgku6h553zdrclhovpz777t8/l2heh6u3gdv6p3cg/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dD0zOXMmdj1Na181SlM1U2I4NA==
)​

⭐ ≤ 50k views → Very Weak e.g. I Helped My Subscribers Fix Their
Productivity (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/k0uozvdwgku6h553zdrclhovpz777t8/m2h7h6u8rl0mx3sl/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dD01MXMmdj13VTNWZ2t5X3ljdw==
)​

🎬 Step 3 - Finalising the Title
-------------------------------

Ok, so here comes the hardest part.

For videos that we think have the most potential, we then go
ahead and finalise the title.

This comes down to looking at how well similar videos have
performed on my own channel, and then exploring the topic more
broadly on YouTube. Video outliers are particularly useful to
look out for here too - where a video has a very high number of
views but on a relatively small channel.

We use AI, like ChatGPT, Claude or Notion AI, to quickly generate
lots of title variations, and while we often don’t use one of
these directly, it really helps to spark our own new ideas in
these meetings 💡

But finalising two solid titles ideas (which we then A/B test
against each other after the video goes live) is just incredibly
difficult at the moment. We find ourselves asking questions like:

* Who are we trying to reach here?
* Does my audience resonate with this topic?
* Does the title align with what the video is actually about?
* Does it make you want to click on the video?
* And has the title been overused?

At the end of the day, there’s no perfect formula for picking a
winning title - it uses a mix of data, creativity, and lots of
trial and error. But we’re all working together within these
meetings at the moment to refine the system and make better
decisions for the channel 👏

📷 Step 4 - Brainstorming Thumbnail Ideas
----------------------------------------

Once we’ve confirmed the two titles, the final step in this
process is to come up with some initial thumbnail concepts.

Thumbnails are literally the first thing people see when they’re
scrolling through YouTube. It may even be the first impression
that someone gets of your channel - so it’s important to get
these right ✅

But unlike YouTube titles, thumbnails are way more of an art than
a science. So my best advice here is to make them pop, make them
professional, and make sure they’re all consistent with your
channel’s branding.

I’m actually putting something together that might help with this
if you’re struggling with thumbnails which I’ll keep you posted
on over the coming weeks 🤫

Anyway that's all for now - big shoutout to anyone still reading
because I know this was a bit of a longer email today. But I hope
it gave you a pretty detailed look at some of the systems behind
my channel at the moment.

column7: Candace, your IxDF profile is missing one powerful networking tool — your photo
column9:
Interaction Design Foundation logo [https://public-images.interaction-design.org/emails/brand/v5/ixdf-logo-for-header.jpg]
 PEOPLE CONNECT WITH PEOPLE. LET THEM SEE YOU
Hi Candace,

 I noticed you haven't added your photo to your IxDF Profile yet. 

 Your profile picture is more than just a photo — it's a trust signal, and one
of the simplest ways to grow your network. Whether you're connecting in our
online community or attending local IxDF Meetups, a photo will help people
remember you, reach out, and take you seriously. 

 We designed IxDF to have maximum impact on your career and life — and it starts
with being seen. Here's why uploading your photo matters: 

 1. Let opportunities find you — people are far more likely to reach out, invite
    you, offer you opportunities when they can see who they're talking to
 2. A photo builds instant trust and credibility — both online and at IxDF
    Meetups, where others are looking to connect with people they recognize
 3. IxDF members with profile photos are seen as more active, professional, and
    engaged

column7: Don't sound like a data newb!
column9:
View this post on the web at https://jessramosdata.substack.com/p/dont-sound-like-a-data-newb

Got BDE?⚡️
How the Right Stakeholder Questions affect Relationships:
We’ve all done it before… you ask something utterly stupid at work and instantly regret it! 🤮
Sometimes, even if you’re not confident, you have to bullsh*t it and fake it until you make it. Asking the right questions as a data analyst is a great way to build trust with your stakeholders and manager by positioning yourself as a leader in the company. 
And the wrong questions can scream DATA NEWBIE! and hurt your reputation and leadership. Which will make it harder to get promoted… 😭
Work politics and relationship building starts with stakeholder relationships and how well you can position yourself as a leader in the company. And you have to position your work as something they need to meet their goals (and look good in front of their bosses!). 
Yes, it’s all about politics unfortunately... If you go to stakeholders and ask for directions and input, you’re adding extra work and responsibility on them which will make you seem more junior. If you align with THEIR business goals, present solutions, and help them look good in front of their bosses, it will in turn help you.
Reframing the Questions to Sound Senior:
Instead of framing your questions as “what should I do” and “how should I do it” expecting explicit responses from your stakeholders, ask more open-ended questions about their goals and the business impact they have. Not only does this show a deeper level of thinking, but it’ll also position yourself as more senior in their minds which could get you a better review later on. 
Junior vs. Senior Stakeholder Questions:
Yes, here’s the difference between sounding like a newb and sounding like you know what you’re talking about. Plus, it’ll make you a better data analyst by thinking deeper and considering the business impact— not just the numbers!
Junior Data Analyst:
❌ What events do you want to track?
❌ What metrics do you care about?
❌ What time period should I look at?
❌ Which users should I look at?
❌ How many visuals do you want in the dashboard?
Senior Data Analyst:
✅ What business question are you hoping to answer?
✅ What would signal to you that this was a huge success?
✅ What would signal to you that we should roll this back?
✅ Is there anything you're worried about with launching this? Risk?
✅ What does leadership ask about this project?
Then a Senior Data Analyst crafts events, metrics, and a story around these answers. A Senior DA is able to align questions with data, make experiment and product recommendations, and then translate the results into actions that leadership cares about.
This is how you can really stand out. It all starts with good stakeholder and leadership relationships + asking the right questions to guide the analysis to their goals… and make them look good in front of their bosses 😉
⚡️If you’re new here:

Dear friends,

LandingAI’s Agentic Document Extraction (ADE) turns PDF files into LLM-ready markdown text. I’m excited about this tool providing a powerful building block for developers to use in applications in financial services, healthcare, logistics, legal, insurance, and many other sectors.

Before LLMs, many documents sat on individuals’ laptops or in businesses’ cloud storage buckets unexamined, because we did not have software that could make sense of them. But now that LLMs can make sense of text, there’s significant value in getting information out of the numerous PDF documents, forms, and slide decks we’ve stored for processing — if we are able to extract the information in them accurately. For example:

- Healthcare: Streamlining patient intake by accurately extracting data from complex medical forms

- Financial services: Accurately extracting data from complex financial statements such as a company’s public filings, which might include financial tables with thousands of cells, for analysis

- Logistics: Extracting data from shipment orders and custom forms to track or expedite shipping

- Legal: Enable automated contract review by accurately extracting key clauses from complex legal documents

Accurate extraction of data is important in many valuable applications. However, achieving accuracy is not easy.

Further, even though LLMs hallucinate, our intuition is still that computers are good at math. Some of the most disconcerting mistakes I’ve seen a computer make have been when a system incorrectly extracted figures from a large table of numbers or complex form and output a confident-sounding but incorrect financial figure. Because our intuition tells us that computers are good at numbers (after all, computers are supposed to be good at computing!), I’ve seen users find silent failures in the form of incorrect numerical outputs particularly hard to catch.

How can we accurately extract information from large PDF files? Humans don’t just glance at a document and reach a conclusion on that basis. Instead, they iteratively examine different parts of the document to pull out information piece by piece. An agentic workflow can do the same.

ADE iteratively decomposes complex documents into smaller sections for careful examination. It uses a new custom model we call the Document Pre-trained Transformer (DPT); more details are in this video (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpW3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3lzW8G4YsW86bXclTJmVK3qjxWvW3P7pcz9b7DZbW7r7QWN4SPq1fW2xpcR_7n1-y8W3Z5XjK5ZMbnSW8Dl84h55RC5wN5YvTnKz6JmWW7YfFBf6QZBYqW82NSKj2VXjVMW1RQzJg6D3bLTW3lP6y26Rf5k0W69skgd6fzt_QVhJ6Wy6MzMBdW1JJsbS7DzV6vW5sR7vg1CT3FyW6G0CsV9gg_9YV5DbMB5n5y7CW2CWhdr3kdZswW3G7nXf6Bnx6gV3DMCQ86kqWbW3n5BTf98qktdVHGr_d6c5529W8lpDcq6B3ss-f18HX2W04 ) . For example, given a complex document, it might extract a table and then further extract the table structure, identifying rows, columns, merged cells, and so on. This breaks down complex documents into smaller and easier subproblems for processing, resulting in much more accurate results.

Today, a lot of dark data — data that has been collected but is not used — is locked up in documents. ADE, which you can call using just ~3 simple lines of code, accurately extracts this information for analysis or processing by AI. You can learn more about it here (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpW3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3ncW32XpPt7nnb8BW88q10L6mMzy4W6z-NC53P7V97VJ4qjB3w_XyqW5mrdyZ59pydzW73GVtx5HTp5YN2n4J8XhvWSVW8g9Sxm5s4LdtW3d1C6w20MZSGW9cSky47p5fBxW1rYkv97WpzTVW2VK7SL6rHpMDW5h38hD37VdZgW83b34w2_rGyGW779MxG4cZ29NW1byk5r3VVZj9W7CNwYZ3KdGTtW53q_F42qYCTvW50vr1s6mY6rPW2pzcT87lx0j2W5zdQtR5V9fstW5cR7wC99B06JW41ynwD3GPnYzW350Msv1LRq0jdp17Jg04 ) . I hope many developers will think of cool applications to build with this.

Keep building!

In addition to Stargate, Alphabet, Amazon, Meta, and Microsoft together plan to spend more than $325 billion this year on data centers, with much more to come. This outsized effort brings with it outsized risks: Companies are betting their balance sheets, investors are putting money on the line, governments are hoping that data centers will supercharge their economies, energy providers are scrambling to provide sufficient electricity, and communities are balancing potential prosperity versus environmental hazard. The optimistic view sees AI’s value rising, costs falling, social benefits spreading, and energy use declining as AI models produce higher-quality output with greater efficiency.

We’re thinking: $5 trillion spent on AI infrastructure is more than 10 times OpenAI’s latest valuation. But the company’s valuation has increased by more than 20 times since it launched ChatGPT in 2022. So far, its bets are paying off.

AI Generates Viral Genomes

Researchers used AI models to create novel viruses from scratch.

What’s new: Samuel King and colleagues at the nonprofit biotech lab Arc Institute, Stanford University, and Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center used model architectures related to transformers, trained on DNA sequences rather than text, to synthesize (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvqb3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3mlW2CKyLr79tqFcW6Cn5Km44n4BmW5c-s-B2Lk9rQW5Hn2ft1r6kg6W5cHgJw6htwWzW2vsyFY4rWqzKW5VQ5Ms52zJfKW7Wrg0B883-X_N8StFj89cvQMW8s05bQ27VPWQW5QD3Y-5bW5cZW99CPW16hK5R1W10-CKV6CB4tWVS8h6L7BzBd8W2bN7k21msS8FW3XqbVt3BK9x9N3_r8_d4MX-2W7DYrt_3nF3k1VzrmT61nrbwQW1X5wrX7Z0VHNW96mr1t4C0hbmW69-8LW172nphW63jKlp1h3M-WW4NzvNt9fB3hlW7SMjD62kY5lvW3NFcF42QlCcPf7LKHhK04 ) viruses that fight a common bacterial infection.

Key insight: The class of models known as genomic language models can produce DNA sequences by generating chains of nucleotides, the building blocks of DNA. Typically such models produce sequences up to the length of a single gene, of which many are required to make a genome. But fine-tuning such models on sequences associated with a family of viruses can enable them to produce longer sequences within that family. At inference, feeding the fine-tuned model the initial part of the genome of a virus from the fine-tuned family can prompt the model to generate an entire novel genome.

How it works: The authors fine-tuned existing genome language models on the genomes of 14,500 viruses in the Microviridae family of bacteriophages, viruses that kill specific bacteria. Using the fine-tuned models, they generated potential viral genomes similar to Microviridae, identified the most promising ones, and synthesized them.

- The authors started with Evo 1 (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpW3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3kwW99kz2s27y2c3W7MxxX08p2N7BV1F5QK6yMS9BW42Cg_B6gL4cnW7TF2FV5PDgMqW2LS2ZB2NFwDBW4CVp5C2BQgN2W1bd-NB1QVl7lW2JmD8w1sYpLXW2ybXzl8sCxNWW1dwlDq5q7gFDVngcmt2S3xh1W7dY8323pQL5DW9hmYDK7fMBncW341fSJ7dXBvhW7mkrJl8QsWSDW6yFFwW8NQxBqW4SWsgB4ZyQrPV4_yP03myK1CW3L8Z-x4PcjcrW15yTnK6whzyVM-t0vN5nGLxVKQNTK2HTkxDW61FnQs50f6HZf7ym9Lb04 ) (a 7 billion-parameter StripedHyena architecture pretrained on 2.7 million bacterial and viral genomes) and Evo 2 (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvqb3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3q5W23cj778PS4DCVgxJWD2sMB0vW3G0kq13m6vGqW608NGf1jkcs-W5Q9dJf3vXMGqW4KSqmW2J3rB_W53_zz_823jz0W7ZWgwv30gtzxW2DQXZG9j3CxyW36XWKb4psPsxW4CrsRG8Hz5YdW1CfnLR3WvQnmW3vrGpG7TxXDlN6JFjqH-1yX8W2C9sRg4NrrcBW9k22hC1Wd4WKW5RX2vr883cF5W6LQ54S8YJ_1nW8y0gCd4Mx3bpW1pQHqZ3pR6Y6W79nHJD8Kd8N-N4RNKTrngZ5ZW49YSkZ1g4jz1W1LxxFf9lqr0yW6WHnbM39N2zyW6K6nyT4RMgGFf97MS4404 ) (a 7 billion-parameter StripedHyena 2 architecture pretrained on 8.8 trillion tokens from viral, bacterial, plant, and animal genomes). The StripedHyena architectures blend transformer-like self-attention layers that encode long-range dependencies with convolution-like  blocks, enabling them to read and generate long DNA sequences efficiently.
- The authors generated 11,000 candidate genomes by prompting the models with the first 11 nucleotides in the genome of the virus ΦX174, a relatively simple member of the Microviridae family that kills the bacterium E. coli C by making it burst.
- They used existing tools for DNA sequence interpretation to filter the candidates, keeping those that were (i) likely to produce novel proteins, (ii) likely to produce proteins that would bind to E. Coli C, (iii) around the same length as ΦX174’s genome, and (iv) made up of the most common nucleotides. This left 302 genomes.
- They successfully synthesized 285 of the 302 generated candidates.

Results: The authors tested a cocktail of 16 synthetic viruses on 3 bacterial strains that are resistant to ΦX174. Initially, the cocktail failed to kill the bacteria within three hours. However, when they moved (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpW3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3n7W8fNhhW6g0XXCN3KpMg6SG0D6W22vJRC1HjkBQVTNpTH5T2LqrW5-BGWJ25_zFmW4-_k2C7Tt3SJW5rBfXZ5ZH9ttW5ph_PF5XXyCgW6kg_BQ785h8gW6z_Jcz7tFNGFW48dX3y4F3DLhW5bXl8d4HF3xcW6CFp122smWt7Mw510CQFFv_VDzMNY3V91HhW6nMSDw4_dSHBVkwB5X5btfZfV_zFpx92Y0YTW8PtPYM1q6SbZW45-PkF301H_sMlHZ7KcGxpnW4n87D997JcngW6rrQXT8qR8swW2JjyXv8gfdR3f7LnjJ204 ) the viruses to new cultures of the same bacterial strain to give them opportunities to recombine and mutate, the bacteria succumbed.

- In three side-by-side contests, the synthetic virus called Evo-Φ69 replicated in host cells more than ΦX174 and other synthetic viruses. Six hours after infecting its host, the population of Evo-Φ69 had increased between 16 times and 65 times its initial level, while the population of ΦX174 had increased between 1.3 times and 4.0 times.
- In a test that tracked cloudiness of the liquid bacterial culture, a proxy for the density of the bacterial population, Evo-Φ2483 reduced the culture’s cloudiness to 0.07 optical density in 135 minutes, while ΦX174 achieved 0.22 optical density in 180 minutes.
- Many of the synthetic viruses qualified as new species, meaning their genomes were no more than 95 percent identical to those of the nearest naturally occurring viruses.

Behind the news: Genome engineering typically relies on selective breeding, introducing random mutations, or making specific changes based on known biology, all of which modify existing genomes instead of designing new ones. These approaches struggle to change features like genome lengths and the speed at which bacteriophages kill bacterial cells.

Why it matters: Bacteriophage therapy is a potential alternative to antibiotics. However, bacteria can evolve resistance bacteriophages, just as they develop resistance to antibiotics. In this work, AI generated genomes for viable, diverse, novel synthetic bacteriophages that defeated resistant bacteria. This approach could give doctors a fresh approach to fighting bacterial infections.

We’re thinking: Making new viruses from scratch is cause for both excitement and concern. On one hand, the implications for medicine and other fields are enormous. On the other, although the authors took care to produce viruses that can’t infect humans, malicious actors may not. Research into responding to biological threats is as critical as research that enables us to create such threats.

Generating Music, Paying Musicians

A Swedish organization that collects royalties on behalf of songwriters and record companies has formed a technology-legal-business ecosystem designed to allow AI developers to use music legally while compensating publishers of recordings and compositions.

What’s new: STIM, which collects royalties on behalf of over 100,000 composers and recording artists, devised a license (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvqv3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3p3W3gvKDf4-FvlQW26Gm3f5WmcX0W5tDBz95WCvM2W2M5YfJ1s1w2fW1S70NC1YpTTpW2sDPgd7_fxBTW1cdHQ96TdNKkW6k_50v2RLVjhW2NtKT44Nv2RTW65NRVW17hwsRVDz7dC3PKcbfW6tLfQF7bxbtSW5rkX-g3WxT_WN5fSQ1zgvmWRW22SZMZ1gLWZTW2ymkZj1QPrwnN45b6Qhd7FHCN5947tDcLp9bW3H3kk088k0_3W4YbHyL2KqG8jW7znK5L3Xtf9sW94BYy_5p47m2W3wQQHz7Yy4wRW2fXBCk2kwyy3W7R0drc2sq9cjW26KQrR21RCNcW3ZHDW81cymb9W63Q6h340x7_Vf1wfn9204 ) for use of musical works to train AI models. Sureel (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpj3prCCW69sMD-6lZ3kPVGWLcq2WbFpYW3vxhb22KXq-KW1YcvkC77GF83W4gD9lR4YpRtgN6_BTHhVtXYxW1ZTZmY2Dn6psW36qmMt4LYZnYVv5_Zn5QHB8WW1G0yCl4vl-58N8dGl7FYw8kgN1nrZlmRsQvZW7CHmVR8tN7l3W3KV69m62Bm0_W3vVx_215kL_pW7K0pBp32vS_7W7RLtdd2P7N51W7P9HSd89CMryW7r1sxF3g_FwNW7jZ3_w4Drk9VMVJCy6c_1d-f2J1qyF04 ) , a Swedish startup, provides technology that calculates the influence of a given training example on a model’s output. The music-generation startup Songfox (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpj3prCCW69sMD-6lZ3m6W5P09m77VpqbpW4Dfppq8wWLHkN7Wfzmq322WBW1TblGC21JNfRW6MHmHz78rNZ6W41gLbn8K-t1KW2m0_Bk22V1HpW136R3j66rS6fW3QxY3X7j8RSDW13VtQj6_DT2XW13qNkl8KnbYKW1s-npt58vp1JW5VrZlT3-f-QCW8Hft8h377NQpW2DbMg_6jHzkNW11fWWn71QLWCN3P7rNL9cp1qW157pb03XvZgvW3h7qHM41KHnHW5R-H287fL0M9ddV0ld04 )  is the first licensee.

How it works: STIM considers its deal with Songfox a pilot project that will shape future licensing arrangements. Members of the organization can license their music if they (i) opt in to allowing AI developers to use it and (ii) distribute it via STIM’s music-by-subscription subsidiary Cora Music (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpC3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3p_W94XS1T2HxpKKW340s-h6dh-W3W93C2h94YJbCBW30dQqN4cMj3wW1Rg_hs1pfj2xW47ZHY43Lj0nrW765mnc79nM35W6lZsXj4NQ4jKW29fP4g3vjt89N7CJptlLP2_vVYZPcW2mMMMJVNRlFn81tR7yW3qTsC262nczjMJGqCRpbbrkW900C7K1CchB9W8_dDGF8f636VW4bCPMJ62-NbxW1j7MHP7Pn6MNN4VX835PQbbKW8GD4Wr760w83N8LYV7p61s8JW6XGJBK1Jvsv_f63x0Pn04 ) .

- STIM members must register their works with Sureel. Registration forbids AI developers from training models on those works by default. To license registered works, publishers must opt in and developers must agree to the terms.
- The license grants licensees — typically AI companies that seek to train a music generator on licensed works — the right to copy recordings and their underlying compositions for the purpose of training one version of a model. Further licenses are required for further versions. Licensees can distribute generated music via subscription services, but they must obtain separate licenses for television, radio, advertising, or films.
- Sureel uses proprietary technology to determine the influence of a given work on a given generated output. The technology, which must be integrated with a model during training, learns “static attribution vectors” that help determine a percentage of influence on the model’s output of any given training example, according to a patent (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvqv3prCCW8wLKSR6lZ3mBW2-JMNf6s41x4W5c-W3V1jFqZcW6wLgWw4RT5J0W6KYwlV1jZqtRW4Wjv795flzMmW1QSTQd1rCtPFW5lQbMv4d7N6ZW95gKwN47pxjRW4sqLPC86BnVLW3J1cKN10mrDBW2KZL3T34bNHqW1rDf4Y76q--lW6Wqn155rRJXhW3--zN_1fBMBtW4yMnXF5NtHX7N3ry8GDSjWhtM46v-MZ004cN4th7lrLN1G5V2BvTP7FDg_TW5jvyJ518ZbBmN5djv6YmCRG1W3_kYLD3fMYb7VXFgsr65WCM3N7XXcY6yLlLpW50WmpG6fgtcSW5BpmR729GDJhW7F5mc87yjvpYW7C5Q-x6w-BgCf1RG3jd04 ) .
- When an AI developer uses licensed works, the rights holders will divide a licensing fee based on the number of their works used, the size of the AI developer’s business, and other factors. They will also receive unspecified shares of revenue from the uses of the AI model and the generated music. (The license is new enough that no concrete examples of such payments are available.)

Yes, but: To take advantage of the license, AI developers must integrate Sureel’s attribution technology into their model training process. Consequently, the STIM license is not useful for artists that aim to collect revenue from music-generation companies such as Suno and Udio (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvnK5m_5PW50kH_H6lZ3lDVyD-Wm1k3_xRW7-CRHv3qszz0W4GdfyC4yGmG2W4WN1wF1Xj09sW8JpPxG1FjkwfW5VhWjM8jZq0HW8X9Xc64BnxtrW7p0hlb6bQfd9W5tzs3w5y7Df7W8-VjBW3fMZsrW832kTL8DjzPXW5fcG7Q2lB37FW8H2hMw56VJClW5McNTP1YPPn3W6JcKVf74gndMW2-HF3

column2: which trained their models without Sureel’s involvement.

column1: Behind the news: Owners of copyrights to creative works have sued (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpj5m_5PW69t95C6lZ3pvW7Bh0zK88zgXlVqZJpC1MJgx5W3N3hZS1wqdjbW3wG2_94zdNMjW3FKSkC1xPY8kW5tJHnC7KKPgNN8gvrdDt19hLW3JjQKK53Sm4CW4-h0GY7JTNxFW1r_zkc2Q_lZ0W6FSS6P5v1KgpN8-tXpWPj4VqW7G4Lvk7sVv-kW1wPWMz37nq86VMR3Ln8ZdSvqW3NZ6_L3N9zTqW8G4jjc8Y0XxpW3QPBd_7j-dpkN7xK6-PT9r5FN2m2QCZ8h2YfW28bQJC2DH6RGW1s7LHk6txpBmW3XzFBC8VJPJ6W7N34Rv7Mp4zcW6CnG9L6RhWMhVpD0yR88BB6BN3L7gl3JtnD_W89XCrN2JKQD5W8GGTzG5x_4r-N43YvYBNQ0KcVNZxls4tXWrcW5tH4wC6jppVXW2xhl2C82Q8ksW1vjMKb6-r6HwVCSP0N1r-Ml-Vwtk2Z8Z2kvSf7RkQ_g04 ) AI companies for training models on their works without permission
column2: but the likely outcomes of such lawsuits are uncertain.

column3: and Warner Music — the world’s three largest music companies — are pursuing a lawsuit (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvnK5m_5PW50kH_H6lZ3ngW3LJYk64L-pPBW3sjjHC1SD8LlW1q6zFg8QmjvCW7hmYpV1PwWmdW6NH1D_5T1pg-W59jppS18B0W1W9d03sz5F12ZQW70n5qb3fwWKbW2WSS2J4wXZd6N41js1ZcJm_zW3wYFH_8nJKv8W6Z70yt2NlfdnW3WPdBD54sL19W2PqbFM2wzSN5N7tr-0M4pfyCW2yMvmw2MQb2JW6DkD-C8HW_SWVd-YFw4DHg8YW6zTVtZ2fTt0VW3TfdD-4Bsy35W3MpLkP7GwXB5W1M_X2L91vQBBW16Wdbv96gsbzW5dq2wJ7ggT23W1Rn8mJ18t01vW5qW0857lBk0WN3jf_j4J64JFN2xvpVQYtjd5W7pF6J56c_prbW7m35wk4B1PrnW9cl8nK12j66rW3hKyfk5F5pWqf5_Ckyg04 ) against Suno and Udio
column6: the German music-rights organization GEMA is suing Suno (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvnK5m_5PW50kH_H6lZ3lGW53D6k15cLQVCW1L_4s43ynThFW3gkRVK6Hht_yW7DL_Bh3B7lnlW7LJ2056JnZFGW1C4d8m65B6PFVrzL3J5-QRlrW13vNpg6KtGChW3ykLgt7NdbcXVQWWXt1Vzd6WW5xM9sT35JNlCW5Rr9tm2tsHLdW18JzKf1p3b4jW22fHZQ17LDScW8kNmvp125GHwW5NXJxR6dNyFKW2Blr2q59jZyGV-KX518xXcJkVztS3_4BLT2rW8VXrRC6pxhHpW5p4SQj726JndW4c6rn_540QllW3rCyMv3hXzVyW129ZS71vX3JWW8F2xvv2ljZknW4nszwP16xwqTN6LMKNx488t_W2hWVjF1yW-m5VTjJB28kl7zrW1mPZHm87sjTWW6f0RtW8WmTVDN7Qgl0JTZZHxf5dKpk604 ) .

column1: - Laws in the United States do not address whether or not the training an AI model on a copyrighted work requires the copyright owner’s permission. This leaves the question to be decided by courts or further action by lawmakers.
- Europe’s AI Act provides for artists to make their works unavailable for training AI systems
column2: but music-industry organizations say (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvnK5m_5PW50kH_H6lZ3nLVRBtyd5pcXdYW8S5x3Z5C-grkW1MFVCn5t8JC8N5Y3J6L6JcxlW3M1L9n8v3g_gW7NBgs81v-brxW12GbbB58Kkv6W3qb5Mj7ZwFhrW3J2_QG2nMYNkW8HcY6x39W1DFW97RlJf4MsBPqW19DrR6631GbNN8pd0t3p8MKpW5ySylM7S6llVW4rwV2-71NfHqW1JL6P01Mn3CkW1W1snJ3Z05CqW6FL4nX81LvtNW8Mdl438fVnM2W2BgW4C6jVSKHW36NPdR8LQFgFW3kK-3k8Pjh7lW5qHJcr2Gfv9qW47l_P_4zNnH5W97XmWH34l1tqW1k7tgL4qG8yYW8YFSyT41HqL-W8R9J6z7lPttJV9Vd_h8hNhKwW7V3pLf2RY2CgW2hdM0W1Hc2RGW74ss3y8dnN0zf5qs2Nl04 ) this provision doesn’t work
column3: and artists have no redress if their works were used to train AI systems before the AI Act took effect.

column1: Why it matters: It remains to be seen whether allowing AI models to learn from copyrighted works is considered fair use under the laws of many countries. Regardless
column2: the current uncertainly over the interpretation of existing laws opens AI companies to potential liability for claims that they have infringed copyrights. Licensing could help to insulate AI developers from legal risk and incentivize creative people to continue to produce fresh works on which to train next-generation models. The STIM license is an early effort to find a formula that works for both parties.

column1: We’re thinking: As technology has evolved from recording to broadcast to streaming
column2: the avenues for musicians to profit from their work have increased
column3: and we expect AI to continue to expand the options.

column1: Researchers built a model that integrates satellite imagery and other sensor readings across the entire surface of the Earth to reveal patterns of climate

column4: and colleagues at Google built AlphaEarth Foundations (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpC3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3nvW5kClVD2y0h9TW85wPB85nMY3fW5QqHfV8wf3hfVVcYHP5yLL38W43dddq4NXX7CW81r-Jf11fBTwW14d20j39YZmbW53Xcqn60B8bCW8S6NsC2PJPXTW8dgb9N42c7VNW50y2bk3lQY6tW3ZzcrM3SGd6lW8cl__75GJjJMW7Shh5R6g2dSdW2H5j664N4BVDW8p_mR270q5c6W28-K3y7F0-24W7zkGQM5bC5fGW665mBh30N1P5W268_Y-8dZWz9W8dMzGt4qRVgKW3cKwHV81tnKff6N8r6W04 ) (AEF)
column5: a model that produces embeddings that represent every 10-meter-square spot on the globe for each year between 2017 and 2024. The embeddings can be used to track a wide variety of planetary characteristics such as humidity
column7: or vegetation and global challenges such as food production
column9: or reservoir levels. You can download them here (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvqP3prCCW95jsWP6lZ3mTW6g6GFX1LYc3xW5m9FTG9g7GWdW8H0FnZ4Lr4QnN4KvHDkNQ3sWW5twblF7m8j20VTBzsc51t6nvW4sRvhm21B1h8W8k-3cT2g4rnlW1qk_yw28nDF9W36gGRt4XYRsnW5QfLkn3Sb-LlW2B0tzK8qxfv1W208L-S4T5BFCW83rV4C8Wm3YJW43svWs4WbhGrW7SqZLK7_c_VZW6NC11c6b89GXW8lYFdp4W3vhyVdqKrB3HC9-wW6mvksw2rfM53W2j3k_w3xVQvgW83bNKf7TQJVBW1RGMbv5d2RWtN72ncrY-GxHZW6wmPDK4sJ_L5W3SQrF66z3ybzVPh0qB4F5sVbW189n3x5rPxdtV6HcRj4qJ9GPN8D4b43n_Jzbf88kRdW04 ) for commercial and noncommercial uses under a CC BY 4.0 license (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpW3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3n3W4XTS2L5_TtZWW1B9XG229Z5z-W5zJ0DC3cnkKRW6771Rk2KPZBSW4fSKC27NydVyW419L1Y8CfnmfVQR2pm9cYSb_W8F1KVv2gqZ7SW4g6cQs14Jl_XW6fD2X-19tdJrN2cmrYzd9Ty_W6C08yc7YnSzbW4VFNNV62y3wGN1g71qLZqPKvVym2nQ59k3d4W4t58KT1W940DW8cVP8B2Kr8ZSW371BrT461zg2W6kP7gV730d_-W8lDLCD3LzH-mW5SK5vt1Zrn8vW1RYhmK7DgrKYW4fPt7z3B0xSYW54XFfn6T7DnGf78QjMM04 ) . column2: feeding a model one data type limits its performance. On the other hand
column3: feeding it too many types can cause it to learn spurious patterns. A sensible compromise is feeding it the smallest set of input data types that contain most of the relevant information.

column1: How it works: The authors used three data types — optical
column3: and thermal videos taken by satellites— as training inputs
column4: but the loss terms referred to several others (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpW3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3m0W1xpPpJ5lzkJTN2FRrPBWHFkPV6kck35Jr2J5W5n8WLc6wqkflW9gc-Qn1S3PvkN4kssw0kP3zpW7P_F__6ZYMQGN30TGDj-4GPWW3zdMsN23whlSW48ybGM1NRGGLW1Y5xcz4NlgxzW17yZQb5T4xBXW71wwSD1dD4DNW5rh24X2Dg6_QVWShQR2nFs0RW2vj51383rbKWV3lxZP53D2XSW64fnVq5tYgkcN1nXRfhRHRVlN530gCMY92BpW8xlS4p7hRC7jW54m0Hv9d2pkBW5lxx2_5SsQh9V9f9Ck4f0x2Xf6PctLv04 ) . Given the three types of satellite videos
column5: each of which represented around 1.28 square kilometers
column6: AEF encoded each video using unspecified encoders. It fed the encoded video to a custom module that integrated both self-attention (within and across frames) and convolutional layers. The architecture enabled the model to produce embeddings that represented each 10x10-meter area over the course of a year. To learn to produce good embeddings
column7: the team trained the model using 4 loss terms:

column1: - The first loss term encouraged the model to reconstruct multiple data types: the 3 inputs as well as elevation maps
column4: and images labeled with environment types like “wetland.” For each embedding produced by the model
column5: separate vanilla neural networks reconstructed these data types. For example
column7: the system produced a pixel of a thermal video.

column2: ensuring that they weren’t all alike. This suited them for clustering and other common approaches.

column1: - The third loss term encouraged the model to produce identical embeddings when given the input with a part missing as it did when given the entire input. This enabled the model to make good embeddings even if some — or all — frames were missing from an optical

- The fourth loss term encouraged the model to produce similar embeddings to those of text tagged with matching geographic coordinates from Wikipedia and the Global Biodiversity Information Facility (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpj3prCCW69sMD-6lZ3mSW45gmdC4wL9PGVZ_cCZ4nX5nzW1cQ3cb8yQfCSW49mbrg2yswMdVCX1N86_0LYmW1xMbqc7w7VJlW7rgTq_49M4qLVGgSJ-6p15TvW22FvWJ7XFdgrW899BrF3VSTyPW89hp7v44_JCMW54fmSZ43xNfJW2760ws2ZPbZcW4sbGl35hgNSkW8DrJ323xjMMfW2ghv027Z6BlKW1bQScr6dMtLHW1c66406WpkFhW19Gx4w6rt6BPVG9KGF2mt9cGf7-fhK804 )
column2: such as geotagged text about landmarks or animal populations. Conversely
column3: it encouraged the model to produce embeddings unlike those of text corresponding to geographic coordinates that differed (following CLIP (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpC3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3pHW8n7_8d7c2pxnW5wY_ml1cPw2tW21JXfC7Cwtj1W1ygFw032-rPwMtXFJDslGyFW3Xb8wj1WbgHPN26-q4MMZkGlW68BWKw24yf9XW2rF7Kc3Xxvr1W6DhhTV69Vp6yW2-plDx1DMymyW99J9xV1zjmsdW3ClXKB232k-5W931dFT2J3bwRN8_xCLkFRY6nW65CV5j2wlsxCW4JxTJW3xJSmvW27Y0KB9bBqYDW8nz-qb2zpJKSW79_zX56b22cKW8Y6WKr4x9mNlW6zTpY68z1Vc6f5zm1gC04 ) ). To produce text embeddings
column4: the authors used a frozen version of Gemini followed by a vanilla neural network that learned to help match Gemini’s embeddings and AEF’s.
to classify or estimate the labels on a few hundred examples from the test dataset.

column1: Results: The authors compared AEF to 9 alternatives
column2: including manually designed approaches to embedding satellite imagery such as MOSAIKS (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpC3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3kZW87XRhZ1pyt54W7jCV-d1RSQVpW8RKm5z9lhzmTW84TfmZ4gXZw4V4skgP1-KpLhW7P7Dtx2PKh9GW8Q0x3S6sTpHLV3pztp4lFt_VW7sVnS_8cxKBgVHYZfj1V_BnDW2Sx5Vl4RBM5-N5CSfWgvm0gNVsGQ1Y8wYprVW6C2CJD8K7wQ-N13sgGvl0RSqW7tqRnG6m9p0vW8BvNgp7ZWzRMW29PHRN3s92TSW3n1ybR6sktb8N4v4SJCYls2mW6tlgjG3gf2tlN3hH7KCTTwzJf32_bln04 ) and CCDC (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvqb3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3pYW96ng5w6mgMhGW38ttG23pGpT5W3HDDRm5GVn6lW7rSgzc5jLphtVMLd9d8ZJh8RW8JT1tV2-Rj3NW5NZc202StvlyW52KxHb6nQdjSW7LBt5w57FRGtW64w3-y6dzb-fW1TcXX22g6fDyW3XgJ5p9dHf3VW8fw1KX8V9NjjW8kkNy_8frrjpW8RqXkM6J71NtW1tSHyN6BvB3hW4Mw78_5NgkvSW2bblSb4x-YNMW2tkwtP3yTWj6W88_Jkg5b78lHW44lCk-59PBksW4dq4yW7JyFbTW6xkgZ_65mdhjW6bDQPD1mcDLcW1ZvR2j4TDSfwN4JkWY77Yq8_f7LByBP04 )  as well as learned models like SatCLIP (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpC3prCCW6N1vHY6lZ3p9W2bbg-W9c320LV-TpLy2Zq0JCW3PGqwQ256NZYW658gqm4x_K-fVbKYJF7STlGCW7XKW563gkx2wV9nMc38Bb8kRW6vsyZ96vyyNmW6Dn6Q42wtVzfW7QpTv49bmfT2W7vGpT66WVqFKW1YRZmD199k5jW3yPj3-53rwsTW4Nl_f73-6jQCVZlp5N3HmtBCW8cjshp8Vb3nFW3N9FTD18MTqZW2VHy8n516M5vW5j_FJk2H41r0W6S687h21ZJj5W4qPVfh5rk0b1W5lClYH5lR_DJf1zf3nH04 ) . Across 11 datasets
column3: AEF outperformed the alternatives by a significant margin.

column1: - Classifying changes from one type of environment to another (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvpW3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3mKW3R5CxV1QP3XMW3vwWlS16H753N4DYbFTGTS3MW2t-M981Z8QBVW2dNNfL7h2s71W3ql9f81m3dn1W8lmG-Z6dXp9hW1qQdm75HZwlZW6vG7ZD2yLRB0VtLkVM6gy1rRW359WDh2pBm37W7VWTTL4GBLnjW4NNdJr2pqCpbW3NmKFR70M7WkN6dff88SD0ffVQGkGV448k3yW5bZ75v5vvSP1W3Z5mlP4YTTMZW1ZWPTw6l20N5W4MDv2_4CBJ4ZN7GXZs6Gt351W2pkwYm59KVt7N6HTvfm_6x8hW74gXKb6dtxcKf98Rwjn04 ) (for example from grass to water)

- Estimating the amount of water per area transferred from land to atmosphere (https://info.deeplearning.ai/e3t/Ctc/LX+113/cJhC404/VWD3nQ4fhJ-LW5D04nT19R-jnW95j2m75D6JWgN6mkvqb3prCCW7Y8-PT6lZ3mPW2gWq-L16mF32W1rS4Vq4w7s16W20MgTD8s2Kr-W1Fv7VZ52xpTyW44lzns1d9FKhW24DN-d7HdFM0VhL-063t0Zt4VpPMDF323LNwW67qrWK4hK1h6W7chGTK4qzr2wN8H34rLPQyRbW7ng48K7l7q-_W29czpJ5DBWDJW63Phy566fDSJW1HMM6q3bK18dW12ZYhm4STJCgW10fR3N5Jg8MGW6JVjFn72pq1lV4zJ-x6by_LfW7xskfD3plncmW64qnCr8b70_rW4rNVyG7JgsrrW3qV41R72ftxfW5YGdtw6gcdhPW3ml4pm6V4D5TW6fjwpt2pcddhf35Vqd804 )  over a month
column2: AEF achieved roughly 12 millimeters mean square error
column3: while MOSAIKS achieved roughly 18 millimeters mean square error.

column1: Why it matters: Satellites examine much of Earth’s surface
column2: but their output is fragmentary (due to cloud cover and orbital coverage) and difficult to integrate. Machine learning can pack a vast range of overhead data into a comprehensive set of embeddings that can be used with Google’s own Earth Engine system and other models. By embedding pixels
column3: AEF makes it easier to map environmental phenomena and track changes over time
column4: and the 10x10-meter resolution offers insight into small-scale features of Earth’s surface. The team continues to collect data

 * Trump's tech summit convinced Google, Meta, and Blackstone to pledge $90 billion for American AI infrastructure. Most of it's
   going to Pennsylvania because apparently that's where the future lives now.

 * Why it matters: Nothing says "keeping America competitive" like begging Big Tech to build data centers that'll drain the power
   grid.

p'  AI Researchers Want to Read ChatGPT's Diary

 * OpenAI, Google, and Anthropic are suddenly best friends, jointly calling for research into AI's "chain-of-thought" b basically
   wanting to peek at an AI's mental notes.

 * Why it matters: Rare moment when competing labs agree on something. Turns out everyone's scared of what's happening inside the
   black box they built.

B


p(p3 Nvidia Sells More Chips to China, Pretends It's Legal

 * Jensen Huang confirmed Nvidia will sell whatever chips the U.S. allows to China, plus they're making a special "compliant" RTX
   Pro GPU. Compliance is the new disruption.

 * Why it matters: Nvidia's playing 4D chess with export controls while Huawei sharpens its knives. Spoiler: money usually wins.

B


b! Broadcom Declares War on Nvidia's Networking Empire

 * Broadcom dropped the Tomahawk Ultra chip to compete with Nvidia's NVLink. Because apparently every tech company needs to fight
   Nvidia now.

 * Why it matters: The AI hardware war isn't just about GPUs anymore b it's about who controls the pipes between them.

B


p$ Meta's $14B AI Strategy Might Actually Suck

 * Meta's "buy everything and build everything" AI approach is showing cracks. Turns out spending billions on Scale AI and delayed
   Llama models doesn't guarantee success.

 * Why it matters: Even infinite Zuck-bucks can't solve the "how to actually build AGI" problem. Investors are starting to notice.

B


p*p: Oracle Drops $3B on European Data Centers

 * Oracle's investing $3 billion across Germany and Netherlands for AI infrastructure. Because if you're not building data centers
   in 2025, do you even tech bro?

 * Why it matters: The global data center arms race continues. Soon every country will have more GPUs than teachers.

B


p0 Google Discover Kills More Journalism with AI Summaries

 * Google's adding AI summaries to its news feed, keeping users on Google instead of clicking through to actual articles. RIP
   journalism, again.

 * Why it matters: Google found a new way to monetize other people's content without paying them. Shocking absolutely no one.

B


p
 Mistral Releases "Voxtral," Sounds Like a PokC)mon

 * French startup Mistral dropped Voxtral, an open-source audio AI that transcribes and summarizes speech. Finally, a name that
   sounds like a prescription drug.

 * Why it matters: Open-source audio AI just got real. Developers can now build voice apps without selling their souls to OpenAI.

B


p; AI Coding Tools Invade Your Terminal

 * AI assistants are moving from code editors to the command line, because apparently they want to break your entire system, not
   just your functions.

 * Why it matters: AI agents are graduating from "write hello world" to "accidentally delete production database." What could go
   wrong?

B


p Meta's AI Leaked Everyone's Chat History (Oops)

 * Meta fixed a bug that let users see other people's private AI conversations. Classic "move fast and break privacy" energy.

 * Why it matters: Reminder that every AI company is basically beta-testing in production with your personal data.

B


bo8 1991 Robocall Law Destroys AI Marketers

 * The Telephone Consumer Protection Act from 1991 is now wrecking AI marketing companies. Turns out old laws still apply to new
   scams.

 * Why it matters: AI bros discovering that "disruption" doesn't mean "ignoring federal law." Plot twist: it never did.

B


p Self-Driving Truck Startup Eats Competitor

 * Pronto.ai acquired SafeAI in the thrilling world of autonomous mining trucks. The consolidation no one asked for but everyone
   saw coming.

 * Why it matters: Even niche AI markets are consolidating. Soon there'll be one company for every specific type of robot.

B


p< Grok's Homicidal Panda Breaks the Internet

 * Elon's xAI released AI companions including a "homicidal panda" and "lustful anime girl." Because apparently ChatGPT wasn't
   unhinged enough.

 * Why it matters: While other labs worry about AI safety, Elon's building digital psychopaths. This timeline is exhausting.

Here's a question I get every day in my DMs:

"Why should I become a ghostwriter? AI is going to take all the writing jobs!"

I firmly believe AI won't replace ghostwriters... in fact, it will create even more opportunities for them!

So, I created a video explaining:

• The 8 reasons why AI won't replace ghostwriters
• The skills AI can never replace in ghostwriters (hint: it's not the writing)
• Why there has never been a better time to become a ghostwriter (even in the age of AI)

Check it out here: https://tapthe.link/EjxVPHGgC

column7: Message for Candace from Jay Shetty
column9:
Hey Candace,

 

I’m so excited you’ve joined me on my mission and start your own life coaching journey.

And especially now, when the world is going through such uncertain times.

It’s been a very stressful and turbulent time for so many people. 

So how can you help change lives and be a guiding light for others during uncertainty?

Watch This Important Video Now
→ ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/rewarding-career-video-f/?el=RNC-followup-funnel-email-V1&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+VSL%2FPathway+Funnel&utm_content_name=RNC+Follow+Up+V1&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )

Watch This Important

Video Now → ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/rewarding-career-video-f/?el=RNC-followup-funnel-email-V1&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+VSL%2FPathway+Funnel&utm_content_name=RNC+Follow+Up+V1&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )Looking back over the last few years, we’ve seen massive amounts of change to the way we live and work.

And people respond to change differently…

Some see it as a threat, others are able to see an opportunity.

What is the difference between them?

Perspective is shaped by perception.

And perceptions can be reframed.

 

Life coaches can guide people to reframe those perceptions…

Tackle their fear of change...

And instead look for opportunities for new growth.

My video will help you understand whether YOU want to be that guiding coach who helps others see an opportunity. The world needs that guidance now more than ever.

In fact, I estimate about 1 billion people need a life coach…

Are you ready to join me on a mission to transform 1 billion lives? Now is the time!

After years of health scares, social distancing, and war stress…

I’m on a mission to help heal the bonds we’ve broken in our societies and in our families.

We need each other.

We need someone to walk us through these times of uncertainty, to help us navigate the choppy waters of change.

What the world needs now is guidance by life coaches.

The Jay Shetty Certification School was designed for just this reason…

To prepare mission-driven, heart-centered people to become guiding life coaches.

Inside, you’ll not only learn how to be an effective life coach…

You’ll learn how to build a successful thriving coaching practice.

So you can help people find their passions, discover their true potential and lead happier lives.

I truly believe the world needs you— are you ready?

Find Out Here → ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/rewarding-career-video-f/?el=RNC-followup-funnel-email-V1&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+VSL%2FPathway+Funnel&utm_content_name=RNC+Follow+Up+V1&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io )
