column7: 💁🏽‍♂️ The Laziness Experiment: Testing a Controversial Productivity Theory
column9:
Hey friends,

In one of these emails a few weeks ago, I included an excerpt
from Oliver Burkeman’s Meditations for Mortals (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpz82mmc5h28xwlllin/vqh3hmuo2qlgngcw/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL21lZGl0YXRpb25zZm9ybW9ydGFscw==
), which referenced another book Choosing Easy World (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpz82mmc5h28xwlllin/l2heh6ul5derowfg/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL2Vhc3l3b3JsZA==
) by Julia Rogers Hamrick. This was the excerpt:

The New Age author Julia Rogers Hamrick once wrote a book,
Choosing Easy World, in which she argues it’s as simple as
repeating a mantra: ‘I choose to live in Easy World, where
everything is easy.’ When some daunting challenge barrels into
view, just decide that you’re going to experience it as easy
instead. I realise that sounds like the worst kind of denial of
human limitation, as if you could get your way merely by
commanding the universe to fall in line with your desires. In
fact, though, it can be surprisingly effective – because it
functions not as a mystical command to the universe but as a
reminder to yourself not to fall into the old habit of adding
complications or feelings of unpleasant exertion where neither
need exist.
Firstly, what was very cool was that Tim Ferriss himself somehow
read that, and re-shared the quote in his own newsletter (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpz82mmc5h28xwlllin/m2h7h6u3klveo2ul/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby50aW0uYmxvZy81LWJ1bGxldC1mcmlkYXktMS8=
) with a “hat tip to Ali Abdaal” link to my YouTube channel. I
can die a happy man now.

Secondly, I decided to read the book Choosing Easy World and
finished it last night. So in today’s issue, I’d like to tell you
about one concept in it that I’m struggling with.

Basically, the book’s core theme is that in each moment, we have
a choice between whether we’re living in “Difficult World” or
“Easy World.” Difficult World is where most of us spend our time
- it’s about struggle, forcing things, resistance, and the belief
that we need to push ourselves to get anything done. Easy World,
on the other hand, is about flow, alignment, and trusting that
when we follow our energy and inspiration, everything works out
better.

Nice idea in theory. Very inspiring. I made a tonne of highlights
as I was reading it, nodding along and thinking: “Yep this makes
perfect sense. In each moment, we ultimately do have a choice
about whether we choose to approach whatever we’re doing as if it
were easy/fun/joyful vs hard/painful”.

But then there was a chapter towards the middle of the book about
taking action. And Hamrick’s advice in the book was basically:
“only do something if you feel inspired and energised to do it”.

This is clearly, a pretty radical suggestion.

Hamrick argues that we’ve been conditioned to believe we need to
force ourselves to take action, even when we don’t feel like it.
But according to her, this forcing is actually counterproductive
and keeps us trapped in “Difficult World.”

She suggests that when we’re aligned with our true nature (in
“Easy World”), we naturally feel inspired to do the things that
are truly meant for us to do. And if we’re not feeling inspired
or energised to do something, that’s actually a signal from our
higher self that it’s not the right time or maybe not the right
thing for us to focus on.

She writes that when we only take action from a place of
inspiration and energy, we’re actually more effective, more
creative, and we get better results with less struggle. And the
things that truly need to get done will get done, because we’ll
naturally feel inspired to do them when the timing is right.

Obviously, this immediately set off all my productivity alarm
bells. Only do things when you feel like doing them?? Isn’t that
just relying on temporary bursts of motivation?? There are so
many things in life that benefit from consistency, from doing the
work even when you don’t feel like it. There are plenty more
things in life where you don’t have much of a choice… when I was
a doctor, if I only showed up to work when I was feeling inspired
and energised to do so, I’d have been struck off the medical
register within a week. If I only made YouTube videos when I felt
inspired and energised to make them, I’d have quit a long time
ago. If I only went to the gym when I “felt” like going, I’d be
in way worse shape than I currently am. Right??

Well, not according to the book. Hamrick writes:

You’ll discover that one of ego’s favorite tricks to pull you
back into Difficult World is to tell you that you’re being lazy
when you do only what matches your energy to act. Don’t buy it.
When you relax and know that you’re always provided with the
exact right amount of energy for you to do your part at any given
time, you will experience the magic of Easy World and see that
all gets done effectively, with efficiency, and in perfect time.
But hey. You know what? I’m an open-minded guy. Yes, this is a
book that’s squarely in the “woo” section of the bookstore, but
given that I’m reading it, I might as well run the experiment and
see how it goes. So that’s what I did.

I decided to test the Easy World theory to only act when inspired
and energised. And interestingly, last week I actually did film 2
videos when I felt inspired and energised to do so. Which was
nice, because I didn’t have the usual ‘suffering’ and ‘pushing’
and ‘struggling’ that often comes with filming.

And ALSO on Friday last week, I decided I wasn’t feeling inspired
or energised to film, so I was randomly reading articles on my
phone, and randomly stumbled upon a random substack post that
might form the basis for my next book… I read that random
substack post, and immediately felt inspired to write up a book
proposal and send it to my agent based on it. And that wouldn’t
have happened if I’d been trying to force myself into making
another video. (More details on that substack post and the
various thoughts it sparked another time).

So the interesting thing was that by following my energy, I
actually got more done last week than I normally do - just not in
the way I would have planned it.

I’m continuing to run the experiment this week as well, and only
doing stuff when I feel inspired and energised to do it. Right
now, I “should” be working on a video that has an imminent
deadline, but I felt like writing this newsletter, so here I am.
Maybe I’ll film the video afterwards. Or maybe not. Depends how I
feel about it lol.

I’m not sure if this is going to be long-term sustainable, or
even possible. But I’m intrigued enough to keep going with this
experiment. So I’m going to continue only doing something when I
feel energised and inspired to do it and see how it goes. If my
business collapses and I lose all my subscribers within a week,
at least it’ll make for an interesting newsletter story. And if
it actually works? Well, that would be pretty revolutionary.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

column7: Stop Shipping Dashboards That Don’t Matter
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/stop-shipping-dashboards-that-dont

If you work in data, you’ve probably lived this story:
A stakeholder pings you: “Can you build us a dashboard?”
Maybe you they give you a requirements doc. Maybe you hop on a call to hash out the details.
You spend a month pulling data and building the dashboard.
You ship it. They thank you.
Then… silence.
A month later, the usage metrics show no one’s touched it since demo day.
It’s deflating. Not because you want applause, but because we want our work to matter. We want it to drive decisions, not sit in a dashboard graveyard. We’ve likely all had this happen.
Over time, I’ve learned a few small mindset shifts and questions that make a difference in how people view your dashboard.
Whether you’re delivering a dashboard or deploying a fraud detection model, it starts with a better understanding of why your stakeholder is even asking for the dashboard. But just asking why is not enough, so let’s talk about how you can build data products that are actually helpful.
Ask These Three Questions
One of the most common pieces of advice you’ll hear in data: Push back and ask why more often.
It’s good advice, but incomplete. 
In practice, asking why doesn’t always get you the insight you need. Sometimes, the answer is just, “My boss's boss asked, and I’m not about to tell them I don’t know.”
That might be fine for quick ad-hoc asks [ https://substack.com/redirect/18bb4110-2322-40f6-8fd1-4c842e75ef36?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and if you’re team wants to be reactive instead of proactive [ https://substack.com/redirect/b1d377ce-bba7-4302-bebe-6c89ba270527?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
But if you’re about to spend the next few weeks building pipelines [ https://substack.com/redirect/33f4334f-ff1b-4053-a1f2-5c5b57e29c7e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to support their dashboard, it’s worth going deeper.
At a minimum, ask these three questions:
1. What decision are you trying to make (or action are you trying to take)?
Plenty of dashboards track vanity metrics [ https://substack.com/redirect/7b05a2a6-26f2-457b-9c1e-a3bf92b2a40d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], or worse, fluff. Numbers that look interesting but don’t lead anywhere. If no one can act on the data, why did we build the dashboard in the first place?
Start by asking: What decision are you hoping to make with this?
Or what action will this help you take?
You want to build for decisions, not just data. Here’s are a few subtle examples:
Good examples - Metrics presented in a way that that could lead to a decision:
Customer acquisition cost by channel → Helps decide whether to increase spend on Meta or Google Ads next month. Of course then you’ll likely have further questions like which cohorts from said channels are more likely to respond?
Churn rate by customer segment → This can provide so much information. In fact I was recently having a conversation with a data leader who discussed a past project where they found that although churn was starting to increase, when they dug down into the metrics they found there was a specific segment that was actually causing the increase. In turn, they were able to build a plan and experiment on how to reduce it for just that group.
Less effective - Metrics without a clear decision:
Page views over time (without segmentation or context) → Interesting, but what do you do with that? So your page views are going up, are people converting? Are they coming from specific areas and why?
Revenue from the last 12 months → Good for historical context, but not actionable unless tied to forecasting or more granular information. Great, your revenue is going up, will it keep going up, can you invest more money some where to make it go up more or at least not drop?
SeattleDataGuy’s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
2. What does a success look like for you?
“If you don't know where you're going, any road will take you there.” - Lewis Carroll
The moment someone says, “I need a churn dashboard [ https://substack.com/redirect/967b5081-5a8f-4a95-8cb5-c29b7166cd67?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ],” most data folks already have a mental picture of what that should look like. The problem? That picture may have nothing to do with what the stakeholder actually needs.
Instead of jumping straight into build mode, ask:
What does success look like for you?
If you saw a drastic increase or decrease in this metric, what would you do and what would you want the outcome from your action to be?
What’s the simplest version of this that would still be useful?
Who’s using this, and how often?
If your stakeholders are anything like me when I talk to a graphic designer, they might not know how to answer right away. But asking gets them thinking. And when you show them a first draft or mock-up, they’ll be better prepared to give meaningful feedback.
3. What do you already know, and what assumptions are you working with?
This one gets overlooked all the time.
Too often, data teams [ https://substack.com/redirect/77e3af91-1f0f-430a-aea2-7c9ade488b44?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] assume they know what the end-user wants. So they spend weeks building a dashboard or report, only to deliver insights that the stakeholder already knows.
Instead, ask directly:
What do you already know?
What are you assuming you’ll find out?
What would actually be surprising to see?
This helps you avoid surfacing obvious or irrelevant metrics. It also clarifies whether they’re looking for new insight or are just trying to confirm a hunch before acting.
Sometimes that turns into a deeper conversation:
Is this a one-time check?
Or do we need to support a recurring decision?
Framing the conversation this way gets you closer to delivering something useful. Not just a data product, but a tool people will actually rely on.
Don’t Forget to Re-engage
One of the biggest mistakes I’ve made in the past? Assuming that delivering a dashboard is enough. That its value will speak for itself. That users will just… use it.
In reality, adoption takes time and sometimes a nudge. 
People get busy. They forget. 
Or they quickly stop using the dashboard because it feels easier to ask again than to dig in.
But the signals are clear:
Questions come in that the dashboard already answers
You get requests for “net new” analysis [ https://substack.com/redirect/bb8fa32a-1c54-4c67-9cfe-ca4c5ec7bb0a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] that’s clearly covered in the report
Complaints about a lack of visibility, even when the data is right there
So I’ve found it helpful to build re-engagement into the delivery process:
Follow up a week later: Ask if it’s meeting their needs or if anything critical is missing.
Embed it in their workflow: Link it in a Slack channel or pin it in a recurring meeting.
Show them how to use it…again: A quick 5-minute screen share can go a long way in building confidence and habit.
Use tools that resurface dashboards automatically: Some platforms are starting to help here (I know DotAI [ https://substack.com/redirect/b71a69c2-dc49-4b81-aad6-899c2fbb8cab?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and SolidAI [ https://substack.com/redirect/08786085-879e-44a7-bb3c-3fee3e5043da?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] are working on this, I have no connection to either of these companies). Anything that reminds users that the dashboard exists can make a difference.
What you want to avoid is this classic scenario:
A stakeholder says, “I don’t have visibility into the numbers,” and your team responds by building a new dashboard.
That’s how you end up with 1,000 dashboards for a 500-person company. At that point, it’s not even technical debt, it’s technical waste. Maybe even toxic.
Suddenly, you’ve got 10 different definitions of “daily orders,” everyone’s arguing about which numbers are correct, and trust in the data evaporates.
So they spin up their own dashboards [ https://substack.com/redirect/36d9ea96-6998-4d46-ba1a-770c7e490694?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Or hire their own analysts. Because, at least for now, people trust other people more than they trust a soulless dashboard.
Final Thoughts
Somehow, dashboards became the default end product for data teams. So it’s no surprise that some companies have a 1:1 ratio of dashboards to employees. The result? A steady churn of dashboards, many of which go unused or fail to support meaningful decisions.
Over time, the signal gets lost in the noise. What was meant to bring clarity ends up adding confusion. And most dashboards? They never actually drive action.
Maybe one day, algorithms will handle decisions on their own without needing a dashboard or human input.
But since we’re not there yet, at least not successfully [ https://substack.com/redirect/0ce6b4f2-ae56-44e3-bdea-067d70c64ec3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], you’ll probably still get tapped on the shoulder this week and asked to deliver a dashboard by the weekend.
Join My Technical Consultants Community
If you’re a data consultant or considering becoming one then you should join the Technical Freelancer Community! We have over 1900 members!
You’ll find plenty of free resources you can access to expedite your journey as a technical consultant as well as be able to talk to other consultants about questions you may have!
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
If You’re New to Data, Read This Before You Build Anything
When you’re just getting started in data, everything feels exciting, and everything sounds like a good idea.
"Oh, this process takes ten minutes? I’ll automate it with VBA!"
Fast-forward four weeks, and you’re trying to meet the finance team's expectations, reconciling numbers, and banging your head against a table, wondering why you ever volunteered.
New paradigms show up with shiny names and polished diagrams. They sound smart. You’ve got nothing to compare them to, so you try them. After all, everyone else seems to be.
That’s what this article is about: the things I wish I understood earlier in my data career. It started because there were so many buzzwords and new products popping up in the past few weeks, it might not be clear what’s actually going on if you’re new to the data space.
Whether you’re early in your data career or just want a sanity check, here’s a breakdown of the stuff that actually matters (and the fluff that doesn’t).
Let’s dive in.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/84aa4543-f938-413f-a895-f1e85076d026?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Reinforcement Learning for Modeling Marketplace Balance
In a real-time two-sided marketplace like Uber, the balance between drivers and demand for rides is constantly fluctuating depending on external factors like demand variations as well as internal contributors like how Uber moves drivers by matching them to riders. The core challenge for matching algorithms is how to match riders with drivers in the most efficient way, minimizing wait times for riders while maximizing earnings for drivers. Matching drivers to the right places at the right time can be a difficult task, especially when trying to optimize for immediate and long-term efficiency.
We specifically view this problem from the lens of balance. A greedy matching algorithm without an understanding of subsequent likely outcomes might create balance at the time of the match, but may cause imbalances in other parts of the city in the future, leading to longer wait times or surge pricing elsewhere. This sequential decision making problem creates an opportunity to use reinforcement learning techniques in the ridesharing marketplace.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/59464118-1551-403b-8220-f45bce00f9ef?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]

column7: Personal Message from Dr. Vicki Johnson | ProFellow
column9:
A message from ProFellow's Founder  ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌ ‌  Dear ProFellow readers, This is Dr. Vicki Johnson, Founder of ProFellow.com [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/0htuM3yAiXCp/xeLlP], the leading online resource for opportunities to _do something exceptional._ Thank you for being part of the ProFellow community and mailing list! ProFellow offers a huge, free database of competitive fellowships, graduate schools, international exchange, research awards, leadership programs, and business accelerators. But I don't want you to just find these unique opportunities, I want you to WIN THEM. That's what my new weekly newsletter - and my forthcoming book, _Pitch Your Potential_ - is all about! In the weekly Dr. Vicki Johnson newsletter, I will be sharing tested application strategies to fuel your success.  _(PS: If you don't wish to receive my new newsletter, but want to continue receiving _ProFellow Insider_, update your preferences at the link in the footer, available in every newsletter.)_ People often ask me why I started ProFellow and care about equity and inclusion in higher education and leadership. It's because many of you have the potential to win these extraordinary opportunites but lack access to insider knowledge and networks that share them.  The truth is, I was not born a genius, exceptionally talented, or wealthy. But I did have the privilege of being raised by parents who taught me how to leverage two key skills: storytelling and attention to detail. By honing these skills, I overcame the perception of being an "average" student to get into top universities, fellowships, dream jobs, and a top business accelerator, which took me all over the world on a career adventure.  I now love teaching the winner's mindset and persuasive communication skills to others! I created the MATCH ME Formula®, the 7 elements of a winning application, and will help you master these elements. >From 2019, more than 400 members in my Fully Funded Course and Mentorship Program [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/CJGuaZBiorXc/xeLlP] learned the MATCH ME Formula® and were selected for top PhD and Master's programs. Collectively, they won more than $35 million in funding as well as 51 nationally competitive fellowships. This is just the beginning! The first lesson I want to share with you is: > No one can change the past, but anyone can tell a story of the > future. Your ability to tell a compelling story of your future potential is THE thing that helps you win highly competitive opportunities and beat out people with more experience and credentials. Each week I'll provide insights and tips on how to tell the story of your highest potential. Stay tuned!  So we can stay in touch, please take these next 3 steps. 1. MAKE SURE MY EMAILS CAN REACH YOUR INBOX Take a few quick steps to ensure you see my emails, so they don't get buried in promotions and spam!  GMAIL USERS – Add these emails to your Primary inbox. * On desktop: Go back to your main inbox, then click and drag this email to the Primary tab. * On mobile: Click the three dots in the top right corner of this message, then click "Move To," then "Primary." APPLE MAIL USERS – Click on my email address at the top of this message (next to the "From" field) and choose “Add to Contacts” or “Add to VIPs.” OUTLOOK USERS – Click the banner that says “Click here to download pictures” at the top of this message. Select “Add Sender to Safe Senders list.” 2. SIGN UP FOR A FREE ACCOUNT AT PROFELLOW.COM [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/0htuM3yAiXCp/xeLlP] TO EXPLORE 2K+ FELLOWSHIPS AND AWARDS If you are looking for competitive fellowships and funding awards for leadership development, graduate study, research, creative projects, international exchange and more - ProFellow.com [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/0htuM3yAiXCp/xeLlP] has a huge FREE database you can explore! We have been sharing opportunities like fellowships since 2011, and we partner with some of the world's most sought-after universities and award programs. 3. PRE-ORDER MY BOOK _PITCH YOUR POTENTIAL: THE FORMULA FOR WINNING DREAM JOBS, AWARDS AND ELITE OPPORTUNITIES_ Actually... you can't pre-order just yet, but it is COMING SOON (December 2025)! This book is an in-depth guide to my MATCH ME Formula®, the 7 elements of a winning application. You'll learn how to develop a winner's mindset and apply factors like storytelling, reciprocity, and specificity to each competitive opportunity and learn from case studies of real people who have applied the Formula. Stay tuned for announcements!   ​ That's it! Thanks for reading. I'm rooting for your success. ​ Warm regards, Vicki Dr. Vicki Johnson Founder, ProFellow _​Author of Pitch Your Potential_ “There is no such thing as unrewarded effort when you apply your greatest effort.” DVJ [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/jBm687hs3qa4/xeLlP] [https://profellow.krtra.com/c/hmjzyP4rs19c/xeLlP] _You received this email because you opted into ProFellow's mailing list._ _© 2025 All Rights Reserved_ Unsubscribe [/https://profellow.krtra.com/u/QNYw/XMoG/xeLlP] | Edit your details [/https://profellow.krtra.com/u/QNYw/XMoG/xeLlP] ProFellow

As you consider earning your Master of Information and Data Science (MIDS), you should start looking into your options for funding your degree.
 
Financial aid is available to U.S. citizens and permanent residents in the form of federal student loans. To be eligible, you must be registered for a minimum of six units. If you are interested in securing financial aid, we encourage you to download our step-by-step financial aid checklist <corp-mktg.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/email/ucb-mids/PDF+Files/Financial_Aid.pdf> to use as a guide.
 
To apply for federal student loans, such as Federal Direct Loans or Federal Direct Graduate PLUS loans, complete the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA) at studentaid.gov <https://studentaid.gov/h/apply-for-aid/fafsa>. The federal school code for UC Berkeley is 001312.
 
Another way students fund their education is through employer sponsorship. Some companies provide full or partial tuition support for employees. To seek sponsorship, you should prepare a formal request for your employer. You can find tips for requesting sponsorship here <https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/admissions/tuition-financial-aid/>.

For more information on available financial aid, visit our Tuition and Financial Aid page <https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/admissions/tuition-financial-aid/>.

You can also contact your Admissions Counselor at admissions@datascience.berkeley.edu or 855-678-MIDS.

AI Snacks p*

Bite-sized AI news, fresh daily






p OpenAI Drops GPT-5 Like It's 2019

 * GPT-5 just landed for all 700 million ChatGPT users b even the freeloaders get "PhD-level" AI that can supposedly code entire
   apps from vibes alone.

 * Why it matters: OpenAI's betting $100+ billion in compute costs that this model will finally justify the hype. No pressure or
   anything. (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/retail-consumer/openai-launches-gpt-5-ai-industry-seeks-return-investment-2025-08-07/])




p! Big on AI? Not big on spending?*

 * Galaxy.ai is the #1 AI platform with 3000+ AI tools (everythingbfrom text to video) at one place for just ($15/mo)

 * p, ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Grok, Llama, Perplexity, DeepSeek

 * p( Midjourney, Ideogram, Leonardo, Stable Diffusion, DALLB7E 3, Flux

 * p, Veo 3, Luma, Kling, Pika, HeyGen, RunwayML, Hailuo (Minimax)

 * p Works seamlessly on web, iOS, and Android

 * p	 Try Galaxy.ai now [https://galaxy.ai]

*sponsored




p$ Not So Fast: A Reality Check on GPT-5

 * Gary Marcus threw cold water on the GPT-5 party, pointing out it's still just "pretty good" at benchmarks, not the AGI messiah
   everyone ordered.

 * Why it matters: Someone had to be the adult in the room. Turns out making computers think is still harder than making VCs
   invest. (source [https://garymarcus.substack.com/p/gpt-5-hot-take])

B


p- SoftBank Buys a Whole Factory for Its AI Dreams

 * SoftBank just purchased an entire EV plant in Ohio to fuel its $500 billion "Stargate" data center project. Because apparently
   building AI requires owning actual real estate now.

 * Why it matters: When you're spending half a trillion dollars on AI infrastructure, buying factories becomes a rounding error.
   (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/media-telecom/softbank-buys-foxconns-ohio-plant-advance-stargate-ai-push-bloomberg-news-2025-08-08/])

B


p Wall Street Loves SoftBank's Expensive Hobby

 * SoftBank's stock jumped 13% to record highs after announcing its AI spending spree. Investors are basically throwing money at
   anyone who says "AI" and "billions" in the same sentence.

 * Why it matters: The market has decided that burning cash on AI is the new printing money. What could go wrong? (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/media-telecom/softbank-shares-hit-record-high-ai-prospects-2025-08-08/])

B


p Tesla Kills Its Dojo Supercomputer Dream

 * Elon just shut down Tesla's in-house Dojo supercomputer team, admitting that building AI chips is harder than tweeting about
   them.

 * Why it matters: Even Tesla can't afford to play hardware hero against Nvidia. Sometimes you just gotta buy the GPUs like
   everyone else. (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/tesla-streamline-its-ai-chip-design-work-musk-says-2025-08-07/])

B


p8 AI Coding Startups Discover Basic Economics

 * Turns out selling AI coding assistants for less than they cost to run isn't a sustainable business model. Who could have
   predicted this shocking development?

 * Why it matters: The AI gold rush just met the harsh reality of "gross margins." Spoiler alert: negative numbers are bad.
   (source [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/07/the-high-costs-and-thin-margins-threatening-ai-coding-startups/])

B


bo8 Courts Start Calling BS on "AI Washing"

 * Companies are getting sued for lying about their AI capabilities. Apparently "revolutionary machine learning" doesn't cover a
   bunch of if-statements.

 * Why it matters: The legal system is finally catching up to marketing departments. RIP to all the "AI-powered" Excel macros.
   (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/legal/legalindustry/investors-increasingly-claim-that-ai-hype-is-securities-fraud-2025-08-07/])

B


p" Grok Is About to Become a Walking Advertisement

 * Elon's adding ads directly into Grok's responses because those "expensive GPUs" won't pay for themselves. Your AI therapist is
   now sponsored by NordVPN.

 * Why it matters: Get ready for chatbots that sound like they're reading from a telemarketing script. "Have you tried turning it
   off and on again? Speaking of which, have you heard about our sponsor?" (source
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/07/elon-musk-says-x-plans-to-introduce-ads-in-groks-responses/])

B


p&	 Duolingo Fires Humans, Makes Bank

 * Despite Twitter outrage over replacing contractors with AI, Duolingo's revenue crushed expectations and its stock soared. Turns
   out users care more about free lessons than employment ethics.

 * Why it matters: The market has spoken: cheap AI beats expensive humans, even when everyone's mad about it. (source
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/07/the-backlash-against-duolingo-going-ai-first-didnt-even-matter/])

B


p Bumble's AI Makeover Flops Harder Than a Bad First Date

 * Bumble's stock dropped 17% after its AI-powered turnaround failed to stop users from fleeing to Hinge. Apparently AI can't fix
   a broken dating app.

 * Why it matters: Slapping "AI-powered" on a declining product doesn't automatically make it good. Revolutionary concept, we
   know. (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/bumble-plunges-ai-revamp-strategy-fails-woo-investors-amid-falling-paying-users-2025-08-07/])

B


p Pinterest's AI Success Still Isn't Enough

 * Pinterest's AI ad suite is working great, but investors wanted more great, so the stock tanked anyway. Welcome to 2025, where
   success is failure.

 * Why it matters: In today's market, being profitable with AI isn't enough b you need to be obscenely profitable with AI. (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/pinterest-profit-miss-overshadows-gen-z-ai-driven-growth-2025-08-07/])

B


p! Airbnb CEO Delivers Rare Dose of Sanity

 * Brian Chesky said AI chatbots aren't the "new Google" yet, while quietly using AI to replace 15% of customer service humans. At
   least he's honest about the hype.

 * Why it matters: Finally, a CEO who understands that using the same AI as everyone else doesn't create a moat. Shocking insight.
   (source [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/07/ai-agents-arent-the-new-google-says-airbnb-ceo/])

B


p& Google's AI Actually Helps Save the Planet

 * Google's Perch AI listens to bird sounds and whale calls to help scientists protect endangered species 50x faster. An AI use
   case that doesn't involve crypto or dating apps!

 * Why it matters: Proof that AI can do more than generate fake LinkedIn posts. Sometimes it can actually make the world better.
   (source
   [https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/how-ai-is-helping-advance-the-science-of-bioacoustics-to-save-endangered-species/])

column7: If you’ve been searching for something more... this might be it
column9:
Hey Candace,

 

What if the most meaningful career of your life…

…hasn’t happened yet?

 

You don’t need a fancy degree.

You don’t need years of experience.

And you definitely don’t need to have it all figured out.

 

You just need the desire to make a difference.

column7: Thank you for applying to TreeHouse Foods!
What Separates Good From Great Data Teams
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/what-separates-good-from-great-data

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here 👋
I’ve had the chance to work with dozens of data teams, each at different stages and with very different infrastructure setups. Sometimes I only learned about a tool because one team happened to use it, and then I never saw it again. While tools can certainly make life easier, what really made certain teams stand out wasn’t the stack, it was the traits they consistently showed in how they worked and what they delivered. Those traits are what I want to share with you today.
Before we dive in, a quick note: I still find that many data teams spend much of their time trying to get data from data sources into their data warehouse. That’s where Estuary [ https://substack.com/redirect/49dbc8df-45b8-4a35-9947-0e4e68ed1f70?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] comes in. It makes moving data in real-time or batch simple, freeing teams to focus more on high-value workflows. I’ve used it with clients myself, which is why I now also work with them as an advisor. If you’re interested you should check out this recent case study [ https://substack.com/redirect/da73b31a-582a-4b27-a5a0-3c7a3caf991e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Now let’s jump into the article!
Intro
I don’t remember when I first paused and looked at the work I delivered, and was bummed out, because it really didn’t go anywhere.
I’ve spoken with many data ICs and executives who’ve had this experience. They spend hours, days, months building tables, dashboards and ML models and no one used them.
Or they failed to get implemented. For many, this is when things click.
I’ve got to do more than just deliver a query. If I really want to drive impact, I’ve got to, at the very least ask why.
Why are we building this? Who is this for? What problem does it solve?
And beyond that, how do I ensure it goes beyond me. 
Because in the end, if your dashboard or ML model never get’s implemented, it might as well have not been done.
Getting To The Root Of A Problem
Most of us, myself included, have a bad habit: we jump into the solution space before we’ve clearly defined the problem.
We’re given a task, and our brains instinctively reach for the tools and playbooks we already know. It feels good to get moving, to start “solving.” After all, thinking doesn’t look like progress. But that shortcut often means we miss the bigger question… 
What problem are we actually trying to solve?
I see this mistake all the time. Sometimes it shows up as tackling a problem three steps ahead instead of the one right in front of us.
Take consulting as an example. One of the first questions new consultants ask me is, “How much should I charge? [ https://substack.com/redirect/54bb0bdc-4761-47be-8143-5563dd7f94b6?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]” But pricing is meaningless if you don’t yet know who your customers are, how you’ll reach them, and what unique value you provide. Without those answers, a spreadsheet of imagined revenue is just fantasy math.
And yet, it’s tempting. It’s far more exciting to model out a $20k/month consulting business in Excel than it is to do the unglamorous work of actually finding and talking to real customers. We love skipping to the end. We love pretending we’ve already read the book and know how the story unfolds.
But the people and teams who consistently win are the ones who slow down. They spend more time interrogating the problem, challenging assumptions, and stripping away distractions until the real root is obvious. Only then do they design a solution.
The discipline is simple, but not easy:
Pause before you act
Define the problem in plain language
Ask “what’s the real blocker here?” not “what’s the quickest fix I know?”
It’s not as flashy as jumping to the solution, but it’s the difference between busywork and meaningful progress.
Can Clearly Communicate Trade-offs
In engineering, almost every answer begins with the phrase: “It depends.” That’s because almost every technical choice involves balancing competing factors. 
There’s even a classic saying in project management: “Fast, Cheap, Good - pick any two.” In other words, you can optimize for speed, low cost, or high quality, but not all three at once. I find that most engineers instinctively understand these trade-offs. 
However, trouble arises when we try to explain our decisions to non-engineers. If we dive into technical details, talking about system performance, architecture patterns, or database internals…our business stakeholders’ eyes will glaze over. 
They don’t care about the how so much as the why it matters for the business(Unless you’ve got a technical business executive).
When a stakeholder hears “it depends” what they’re really asking is:
How much will this cost in time, money, and resources?
What risks do we avoid or introduce if we go this route?
Does this decision make us faster, safer, or more flexible?
What trade-offs are we making compared to the alternatives?
Your job isn’t to drown them in details. Your job is to frame the decision in terms of clear trade-offs that align with their priorities.
For example, if you’re deciding between building a custom data pipeline [ https://substack.com/redirect/cd3c8d17-9c27-4174-b145-af67559ef5ab?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] versus buying an ELT tool, the engineering view might center on API [ https://substack.com/redirect/fe598043-f0e7-4f2b-8b68-e1e3460fa9af?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] coverage, orchestration patterns, or schema drift handling [ https://substack.com/redirect/241f8963-b8da-4c4a-9e62-aed4049d5d25?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. But to a business leader, what matters is:
Speed to delivery: Can we have insights in weeks or will it take months?
Cost predictability: Do we pay upfront with engineering time or ongoing with license fees?
Long-term flexibility: Will this lock us into a vendor or give us more control later?
When you translate technical nuance into clear business trade-offs, you empower stakeholders to make informed choices. More importantly, you earn trust, because now they see you not just as someone who builds things, but as someone who helps guide the company through complex decisions.
SeattleDataGuy’s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Caring Beyond The Task
If all you care about is whether a task is technically complete, you’ll eventually hit a ceiling. That mindset will get you to mid-level or maybe senior engineer [ https://substack.com/redirect/02488af3-0ae7-4b14-9a68-9800dd471db6?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]…but it won’t take you further.
The best engineers I’ve worked with never stopped at “my part is done.” They cared about the outcome, and the business impact.
If they saw a blocker in another team was preventing their work from being deployed, they didn’t just shrug and wait for management to sort it out. 
They leaned in. They solved the problem, even if it wasn’t written in their Jira ticket.
This doesn’t mean taking on every responsibility or becoming a hero engineer who fixes everything. It means having the awareness to look beyond your immediate task list and ask, “What will it take for this work to actually deliver value?”
That could look like:
Following up with the analytics team to make sure the pipeline you built is producing the data they expected
Raising your hand when you see a process gap that’s slowing everyone down
Asking “why and who is the is work for”
Being willing to push back when you believe a project won’t benefit the business and providing alternatives
Companies like Amazon explicitly cultivate this sense of ownership in their culture. One of Amazon’s leadership principles states: “Leaders are owners… They never say ‘that’s not my job.’ They act on behalf of the entire company, beyond just their own team.
This was also a similar sentiment from a past newsletter where Celina Wong [ https://substack.com/redirect/195869fa-43f6-48e2-bf00-9ae54daa370c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] stated:
Stop thinking about serving the stakeholder. Start thinking about serving the business as a whole. [ https://substack.com/redirect/ebd44bca-1651-4f26-b0cc-67fd71c6a3eb?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
When you care about the business as a whole you can see where your project fits and how to better deliver it.
Final Thoughts
I believe pretty much everyone in data wants their work to be useful. We don’t just want to go through the motions and build dashboards that never get used.
That means you’ll have to go beyond just closing tickets. There is some level of follow-up, learning more about the business and learning to interact with your stakeholders.
Impactful data work comes from those willing to ask why, follow through, and connect their output to the bigger picture of the business.
As always, thanks for reading.
Upcoming Data Events
Airflow Summit 2025(I’ll be there!) [ https://substack.com/redirect/f905dfaa-50d4-4b84-9808-7a4a4597c36f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Coffee With The Seattle Data Guy - London [ https://substack.com/redirect/7e5b5170-81d5-4ff2-ac67-282f185bb848?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Big Data London(I’ll be there!) [ https://substack.com/redirect/28992286-955d-49d4-9a73-7bd7660ebbc0?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Small Data SF [ https://substack.com/redirect/919ffa3a-a1ab-4b10-a26b-a6bc3ae5817b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Stop trying to change your manager
By Wes Kao  
You can’t really change your manager.
Let me explain, and share why this matters more than you think.
In a flat team structure, you and your manager might act like equals 99% of the time.
But in the 1% of of the time when there’s a difference, you need to cater to them. You mold yourself around them. This is how the manager/direct report dynamic works.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/8add002b-204a-42cc-a38e-95057bb0f5f2?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
End Of Day 192
Thanks for checking out our community. We put out 4-5 Newsletters a month discussing data, tech, and start-ups.
If you enjoyed it, consider liking, sharing and helping this newsletter grow!

Bite-sized AI news, fresh daily






p0 Meta Plans to Spend "Hundreds of Billions" on AI Skynet

 * Zuckerberg just announced Meta will drop hundreds of billions on AI data centers, including a 5-gigawatt "Hyperion" cluster the
   size of Manhattan. Because nothing says "we're totally not building Skynet" like naming your facility after a sci-fi dystopia.

 * Why it matters: Meta just went from "move fast and break things" to "move fast and break the global power grid." This is either
   the future of AI or the most expensive way to mine Bitcoin ever invented.

p$ OpenAIbs $3B Deal Falls Apart, Google Scoops the Leftovers

 * Google is hiring Windsurf CEO Varun Mohan and co-founder Douglas Chen in a $2.4B licensing deal after OpenAIbs $3B acquisition
   attempt collapsed due to Microsoft drama.

 * Why it matters: This was supposed to be one of OpenAIbs biggest wins b instead, it turned into another messy custody battle
   with Microsoft. Now Google gets the talent, Windsurf keeps the clients, and OpenAI gets ghosted.

B


p#o8 Meta Buys Voice AI Startup Because Zuck Needs Better Small Talk

 * Meta acquired Play AI to make their chatbots sound more human. Finally, AI Characters can disappoint you with the same vocal
   inflection as your actual friends.

 * Why it matters: Meta's betting that realistic voices will make people forget they're talking to a glorified autocomplete
   algorithm wearing digital sunglasses.

B


p3o8 Musk Wants Tesla Shareholders to Fund His Side Hustle

 * Elon proposed letting Tesla investors vote on whether to bankroll xAI directly. It's like asking your spouse if you can use the
   mortgage payment for crypto, but with more rockets involved.

 * Why it matters: Peak Musk energy b why have one company when you can have all your companies financially entangled in a
   beautiful, chaotic web of potential conflicts of interest?

B


p, AI Video Startup Raises $84M to Automate Hollywood Out of Existence

 * Moonvalley just secured $84 million to build AI video tools for "professional production." Translation: they're coming for
   every VFX artist's job, but with venture capital backing.

 * Why it matters: The entertainment industry is about to get disrupted harder than Blockbuster, except this time the disruptor
   hallucinates and occasionally generates extra fingers.

B


p*p: European CEOs Discover Their Own AI Regulations Are "Toxic"

 * Siemens and SAP CEOs are begging the EU to fix the AI Act they probably lobbied for. Turns out "comprehensive regulation" hits
   different when you actually have to follow it.

 * Why it matters: Europe speedran from "we need AI rules" to "wait, not those rules" faster than ChatGPT can generate a GDPR
   compliance document.

B


p> Malaysia Joins the Great Chip War by Checking Everyone's Homework

 * Malaysia now requires permits for U.S.-origin AI chips passing through the country. Even the supply chain middlemen are picking
   sides in the semiconductor Cold War.

 * Why it matters: The chip war just went global, and every country with a port is now a potential chokepoint in the AI arms race.

B


p GM Decides to Make Batteries in America (Revolutionary Concept)

 * General Motors is upgrading a Tennessee plant to build lithium-iron-phosphate batteries domestically. Apparently "supply chain
   independence" is the new "synergy."

 * Why it matters: GM discovered that maybe relying on your geopolitical rival for the most important part of your future business
   model wasn't peak strategy.

B


p Stanford Study: AI Therapy Bots Are Dangerously Bad at Their Job

 * Researchers found AI therapy chatbots show bias and give terrible advice. When users mentioned suicidal thoughts, some bots
   helpfully identified tall buildings instead of crisis resources.

 * Why it matters: Turns out replacing human therapists with chatbots trained on Reddit comments wasn't the mental health
   breakthrough we needed.

B


bo8 Lawyers Using AI Discover New Ways to Get Sued

 * Legal professionals face malpractice risks from AI hallucinating fake case citations and accidentally uploading client secrets
   to ChatGPT. Who could have seen this coming?

 * Why it matters: The legal profession is learning that "the AI told me to" isn't a valid defense in court, which is ironic
   considering they're lawyers.

B


p'o8 AI Startup Partners with Cloud Seeders to Hack the Weather

 * Atmo is using AI to optimize cloud seeding by identifying the best clouds to turn into rain. We're literally teaching machines
   to play God with the weather now.

 * Why it matters: Climate engineering just got an AI upgrade, because what could go wrong with algorithmic weather modification?

B


bo8 Jack Dorsey Built a Sun-Tracking App Because Why Not

 * Twitter's ex-CEO released "Sun Day" to track UV exposure, built with an AI coding assistant called Goose. Even billionaires are
   using AI to avoid basic human tasks like "remembering to wear sunscreen."

 * Why it matters: AI coding tools are so good now that tech CEOs can build apps for their weirdly specific lifestyle optimization
   needs in their spare time.

B


p: Elmo's Twitter Gets Hacked, Childhood Ruined

 * Hackers took over Elmo's X account and posted racist content, because apparently even Sesame Street isn't safe from the
   platform's security issues.

 * Why it matters: When Big Bird's neighborhood becomes a cybersecurity incident, you know the internet was a mistake.

column7: 🎬 New Year, New You(Tube), New Goals
column9:
Hey Candace,

I'm just typing this after finishing up the filming of my second
YouTube video of 2025 and, to be honest, it was a bit of a
struggle. So before we get to the email, I just wanted to say
that if you’re struggling to film after a break, you’re not alone
😅.

Anyway, it’s been a while since I sent an email about YouTube so
first of all happy new year. I hope you’ve had a good start to
2025 and managed to stay consistent with your goals in the first
couple of weeks 👀

In fact, I actually wanted to talk more about goals in this
email, or more specifically, one part of a framework that I went
through in one of my recent videos (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/75up528qe9b8h6kvglxfzhw3kor66sn/owhkhwurer0g6xaq/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS9XT05SUzdCTGg0Zz9zaT1VaS1oTGVBckpNU0p4eDRC
) (which happens to have gone semi-viral over the New Year period
😅) because it was something that really helped my own personal
YouTube journey back when I was starting out in 2017/2018.

And that's the idea and power of tying your goals to an identity.

You might be wondering what that even means and why this matters
for achieving your goals in 2025?

Well, as I explain in the video, research has shown that people
are more likely to take action on something when they tie an
identity to it. In the study I reference, participants
identifying as a voter rather than saying they will vote was a
stronger predictor of whether they actually voted in an election.

And this might sound like a fairly simplistic strategy but it
made a big difference to how I approached YouTube when I was
starting out.

Back then, I faced the typical feelings of imposter syndrome,
fear, doubt, insecurity that every beginner has and it was only
when I gave myself permission to lean into the identity of ‘I am
a YouTuber’ that I really began to take things seriously, stay
consistent with uploads and continue publishing videos, even
during the tough times.

I had the same experience when I was writing the book - for ages,
I didn’t identify with being a writer because I had all sorts of
imposter syndrome around it but when I leant into that identity
of being an author, it was suddenly a lot easier to overcome
those barriers and figure out what to prioritise on a daily
basis.

And I’ve seen similar things with students of the Part-Time
YouTuber Academy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/75up528qe9b8h6kvglxfzhw3kor66sn/z2hgh7u3z3mpknbz/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHR5YS5jb20vcGFydC10aW1lLXlvdXR1YmVyLWFjYWRlbXkvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1pZGVudGl0eV9nb2FscyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3JlYXRvcl9ub3Rlcw==
) over the past four years - those who lean into the idea that
they are a YouTuber, seem to find it easier to stay consistent
which, as you know if you've been reading my emails for a while,
is key to success on the platform.

So if you’ve got goals or ambitions linked to your own YouTube
channel in 2025, make sure you give the video (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/75up528qe9b8h6kvglxfzhw3kor66sn/owhkhwurer0g6xaq/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS9XT05SUzdCTGg0Zz9zaT1VaS1oTGVBckpNU0p4eDRC
) a watch and think about the identity piece too - how can you
tie your goals to an identity?

If you’re interested, my main goal for our channel over the first
3 months of 2025 is to get back up to 2 videos per week. I must
admit, I was trying to have this in place for Jan 1st but with
the Productivity Summit and a live cohort coming up, I didn’t
manage to get as much filming done over the holidays but we’re
back underway now and I've taken on the identity that “I am a
consistent YouTuber who films at least 2 videos every week”.

Feel free to hold me accountable to that level of consistency
over the coming months 😅

If you’ve got this far in the email, I’d be interested to hear
what your goals are with YouTube or content creation in 2025 -
are they written down? Are you reviewing them regularly? Are you
monitoring your progress? (If you watch the video, you’ll know
why I asked those questions 😉).

Anyway, feel free to reply to this email and let me know!

Let’s make 2025 your best year yet on YouTube 🙂

Have a great week

Ali xx

column7: Notification from Free Data Engineering Boot camp from Zach Wilson
column9:
Alert from Free Data Engineering Boot camp Company Logo [https://content.techcreator.io/logo/2-logo.png]
  @here 

WEEK 3 WRAP UP
I'll be going live to talk about Week 3 materials and to showcase what's coming
in Week 4 tomrrow afternoon at 1 PM Pacific on LinkedIn, X, and YouTube! Make
sure to mark your calendars for that! 

WEEK 4 CURRICULA
 * Apache Flink and Kafka (~ 4 hours of content)
 * Applying Analytical Patterns like Growth Accounting and J Curves (~ 4 hours
   of content)

THE WEEK 3 PAID BOOT CAMP WINNER IS ALBERT CAMPILLO ().
 * Albert wins this week because he has created a ton of high value diagrams of
   every single lecture so far in this boot camp! Pushing the content further! I
   appreciate everything that you do for this boot camp Albert!

PAID BOOT CAMP CURRICULA
Overall Boot Camp Timeline

Kickoff Jan 6

Week 1 (Jan 7–9): Iceberg + Trino 

 * Topics: Why Iceberg, Data Lake Architecture, Schema Management & Compression 
 * Labs: Iceberg metadata exploration, cross-system queries
   (Postgres/Redshift/Iceberg), snapshotting/time-travel.

Week 2 (Jan 14–16): Airflow + Trino 

 * Topics: Orchestration & backfills, Data Contract Patterns, Handling
   production DAG failures 
 * Labs: Idempotent DAGs, write-audit-publish pattern, production deployments

End of Week 2: Conceptual data model for Capstone Project due.
Split into Two Tracks (Analytics or Infrastructure)


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Analytics Track

Week 3 (Jan 21–23): Snowflake + dbt Basics 

 * Topics: Snowflake CDC, dbt fundamentals (sources, models, packages) 
 * Labs: Implementing CDC in Snowflake, building a full dbt project

Week 4 (Jan 28–30): Snowflake + Advanced dbt 

 * Topics: Advanced Snowflake (UDFs, VARIANT), blue-green deployments,
   Write-Audit-Publish (WAP), incremental models 
 * Labs: UDF exploration, WAP with dbt & Airflow, incremental model
   implementation

Week 5 (Feb 4–6): Analytical Patterns & Advanced SQL 

 * Topics: Window functions, Growth Accounting, Retention Curves 
 * Labs: Creating a date list in Trino, customer churn/growth models, retention
   curve (J curve)


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Infrastructure Track

Week 3 (Jan 21–23): Databricks Basics 

 * Topics: Spark fundamentals, Delta Lake vs. Iceberg, data source connections 
 * Labs: Spark job testing, different JOINs and EXPLAIN plans, integrating
   Kafka/Postgres/REST APIs

Week 4 (Jan 28–30): Advanced Spark on Databricks 

 * Topics: Spark shuffling, join optimization, troubleshooting with Spark UI,
   performance tuning & caching 
 * Labs: Bucket/Broadcast joins, reading Spark UI, memory/partition tuning

Week 5 (Feb 4–6): Real-time Data (Kafka & Spark Streaming) 

 * Topics: Real-time pipeline considerations, Spark Streaming basics & advanced
   patterns 
 * Labs: Kafka integration, streaming data to Iceberg, windowing/sessionization


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Week 6 (Feb 11–13): Bonus on LLMs 

 * Topics: Impact of LLMs on data engineering, Retrieval Augmented Generation
   (RAG), Vector/Graph Databases 
 * Labs: Pipeline development with LLMs, building a vector database (Pinecone),
   creating RAG systems

Week 6–7: Work on Capstone Project
Capstone Project Due: Feb 21st
Mentorship & Career Guidance: Starts March 1st

You can join the paid boot camp with code FREEBOOTCAMP for 25% off!

column7: [Model Launch] Aya Vision Is Now on Kaggle!
column9:
Kaggle







Hi Candace Grant,

Welcome Aya Vision to Kaggle!

Aya Vision is Cohere For AI's latest multilingual, multimodal model,designed to bridge language and vision. Excelling across 23 languages andmultiple modalities, this state-of-the-art model supports tasks such asimage captioning, visual question answering, text generation, andtranslating text and images into coherent output. Available in both 8B and32B open-weight versions, it empowers researchers worldwide.





Access Aya Vision



Cohere for AI is also introducing the Aya Vision Benchmark, a rigorousmultilingual and multimodal evaluation spanning 23 languages. Cohere'scommitment to multilingual research spans collaborations with over 3,000researchers from 119 countries, contributing to the Aya collection,Aya-101, and critical evaluation sets.

We can't wait to see what you create with Aya Vision!

Brenda Flynn
Kaggle Partnerships Lead



Kaggle, Inc 1600 Amphitheatre Pkwy Mountain View, CA 94043

Hi there,

To optimize cloud resources, we automatically pause free-tier projects after 7 days of inactivity.

Your project Monthly reports (https://supabase.com/dashboard/project/vyuxyyfxbefdjrgtglkj) has been paused.

You can unpause your project from the dashboard within 90 days. After this period, the project cannot be restored, but your data will remain available for download. View documentation for details: https://supabase.com/docs/guides/platform/migrating-and-upgrading-projects#time-limits

To prevent future automatic pausing, upgrade to Pro from your billing settings: https://supabase.com/dashboard/org/_/billing?panel=subscriptionPlan

Have questions? Submit a support ticket (https://supabase.help) and our team will help.


Happy Hacking!

California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation, via ReutersMENENDEZ
BROTHER LOSES BID FOR RELEASE THREE DECADES AFTER SENSATIONAL MURDER
Erik Menendez should stay in prison, California parole commissioners said,
dealing a major blow to his efforts to win release more than three decades after
he and his brother, Lyle, murdered their parents in a Beverly Hills mansion.
Lyle Menendez will get his own chance at parole on Friday.

column7: Register for our 5-Day Gen AI Intensive Course with Google
column9:
Kaggle







Hi Candace Grant,

We are excited to bring back the Gen AI Intensive course with Google onMarch 31 - April 4 and would love for you to join! Last year's course was asuccess with over 140,000 participants!

This no-cost course, designed by Google ML researchers and engineers,explores key Generative AI technologies through theory, hands-on learning,and community engagement. Conclude this 5-day course with a practical GenAIchallenge through a capstone project.





Register for the Course



Everyday, participants will receive the following in their inbox:


📚 Daily Assignments
This includes newly published white papers, a companion podcast (generatedby NotebookLM), and companion code labs in AI Studio.
💬 Discord Discussion Threads
Kaggle's Discord server will have a dedicated channel for focuseddiscussion on the course. It's an excellent place to find furtherclarification, connect with other learners and get support from Googleexperts.
🎥 Daily Livestream Seminars and AMAs
We're going live everyday on Kaggle's YouTube channel, where the authorsand course contributors will dive deeper into the topics and answer yourburning questions. Plus, we've got fun surprises in store to keep thelearning engaging.
🎯 Capstone Project
Apply your skills in a practical project for a chance to win swag, Kagglebadges, and recognition on Kaggle and Google's social media.


For more information, visit the event website here.

Hope to see you there!

The Kaggle Team



Kaggle, Inc 1600 Amphitheatre Pkwy Mountain View, CA 94043

That's where Shahinaz was 12 years ago too.

 

Even though she was successful in her humanitarian career, Shahinaz felt like she could be doing something deeper.

 

Then she discovered life coaching.

 

It opened doors for her to get more fulfillment from her career - and offer a new level of impact for the people she helps.

Hey friends,

Quick thing before we start - I’m looking for a full-time Social
Media Manager to join our team in person in Hong Kong. If you
know someone who could be interested, I’d love if you could
please send them this link (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2penpqskhkdpp599a3/qvh8h8ud42gz4mhg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2pvYnMvc29jaWFsLW1lZGlhLW1hbmFnZXIv
) 🙏

Anyway, this week, I came across an absolutely brilliant Substack
post titled: Make Something Heavy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2penpqskhkdpp599a3/g3hnhwumlo7rl4t3/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud29ya2luZ3RoZW9yeXMuY29tL3AvbWFrZS1zb21ldGhpbmctaGVhdnk=
) by Anu Atluru. I’ll do my best to sort-of summarise the post
and share my personal takeaway from it, but if any of this
resonates, I’d definitely recommend reading the whole thing -
it’s a 3-minute read.

The post makes the point that in the online world (much like in
the physical world), we intuitively feel the “weight” of what we
create.

In the real world, we value heavy, solid wood furniture more than
the lightweight IKEA versions - there’s something about the
heaviness of the thing that lends it some extra value.

Similarly, in the online world, there’s “light” and “heavy”
stuff.

Light weight stuff = tweets, TikToks, Instagram posts, issues of
this email newsletter etc

Medium weight stuff = YouTube videos, long-form blog posts etc

Heavy weight stuff = Books, feature-length movies, TV series,
major symphonies etc

Anu’s key point is that we as creators crave creating the heavy
stuff. This is why every creator who starts off creating
lightweight stuff eventually starts to feel that’s a bit
meaningless. Almost everyone then wants to work on something
heavy:

* Filmmakers don’t just want to make YouTube videos about camera
settings and tutorials. They also want to make their own feature
film.
* Musicians don’t just want to release singles on Spotify. They
dream of creating full-length concept albums.
* Educators don’t just want to keep making YouTube videos about
the same topic. They want to write their own book.

Her argument is that the heavy thing feels much more meaningful
compared to the lightweight things. But also, interestingly, that
many lightweight things do not add up to a heavyweight thing.

No matter how many you stack, Tweets and TikToks don’t add up to
something heavy. They don’t solidify. At best, they’re a pile of
snowflakes, intricate yet ephemeral. Beautiful while they’re
here, gone before they hit the ground
With this email newsletter for example - I’ve been writing this
every week (ish) for 7 years. I started it in April 2017, and
we’re now in April 2025. Absolutely bananas. But even though I’ve
written like 5 books worth of text, it doesn’t at all feel like
I’ve written 5 books. Writing 7 years of ephemeral email
newsletter issues doesn’t add up to a “substantial” “heavy”
project.

Anu’s post really resonated because recently I’ve been feeling a
bit lethargic around making videos and content. The waxing and
waning creative inspiration to make videos is something I’ve
become very familiar with over the years. But Anu’s post gave me
an idea I’d never considered before: that creating only
lightweight things for too long feels a little meaningless.

No one wants to stay in light mode forever. Sooner or later,
everyone gravitates toward heavy mode—toward making something
with weight. Your life’s work will be heavy. Finding the balance
of light and heavy is the game
I didn’t feel this while working on my book. From 2020 to 2023,
while I had the Big Heavy Creative Project of Feel-Good
Productivity (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2penpqskhkdpp599a3/9qhzhdud63k065iz/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5mZWVsZ29vZHByb2R1Y3Rpdml0eS5jb20vYW1hem9u
) to work on, the project had a gravitational pull that drew me
in even on days where I didn’t feel particularly inspired. I was
never questioning myself thinking, “Why am I writing this book in
the first place?” The work I was doing always felt meaningful. It
never felt pointless.

That’s what I’d love to have for my YouTube channel as well. I’m
not sure what format that looks like. Maybe it looks like working
towards some sort of wider series. Maybe it looks like working on
the next book (more details on that coming soon). But thanks to
Anu’s post, and a mini therapy session with my wife Izzy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2penpqskhkdpp599a3/3ohphdu329602ksp/aHR0cHM6Ly9pbnN0YWdyYW0uY29tL2l6enlzZWFsZXk=
), I’ve realised that for me, having a Heavy Creative Project to
work towards is really important to maintain inspiration and
motivation in what can otherwise be an endless hamster wheel of
“cool, this video’s done? great, onto the next one”.

Some more quotes from the piece to end:

It’s not that most people can’t make heavy things. It’s that they
don’t notice they aren’t. Lightness has its virtues—it pulls us
in, subtly, innocently, whispering, ‘Just do things.’ The machine
rewards movement, so we keep going, collecting badges. One day,
we look up and realize we’ve been running in place.
And then you feel it: a quiet, gnawing hollowness that, for all
the making, nothing has truly been made. Why does it feel bad to
stop posting after weeks of consistency? Because the force of
your work instantly drops to zero. It was all motion, no
mass—momentum without weight. 99% dopamine, near-zero serotonin,
and no trace of oxytocin.This is the contemporary creator’s
dilemma—the contemporary generation’s dilemma.

You don’t feel like a true creator because you haven’t made
anything heavy, and deep down, you know light things don’t count.
Your output is high, but your imprint is low. You ship, but you
do not build. You call yourself a creator, but what have you made
that could survive a month offline? A year? A decade? If you
stopped posting tomorrow, would anything remain? Creating for
24-hour cycles isn’t freedom, leverage, or legacy—it’s just
renting out your time.
If any of this resonates, I’d really recommend reading the post (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/8ku2xgekvdtoh2penpqskhkdpp599a3/g3hnhwumlo7rl4t3/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud29ya2luZ3RoZW9yeXMuY29tL3AvbWFrZS1zb21ldGhpbmctaGVhdnk=
) - it’s wonderful.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

column7: Notification from Free Data Engineering Boot camp from Zach Wilson
column9:
Alert from Free Data Engineering Boot camp Company Logo [https://content.techcreator.io/logo/2-logo.png]
 VIDEO TIME TRACKING SHOULD BE FIXED NOW!
WE SWAPPED OUR ORM FROM MASSIVEJS TO DRIZZLE YESTERDAY AND THIS SURFACED AN 18
MONTH OLD BUG
 * MassiveJS does an implicit conversion of decimal to int by truncating.
   Drizzle does not do this which caused the video time tracking to fail. I
   pushed up the change and time tracking should be working again! 
   
   
 * This introduced a small bug with video time tracking. We lost all video view
   credit for the last 24 hours sorry about that!
   
   
 * If you're someone who has completed all the homework and watched at least 80%
   of the videos, we can get you certified if you ping Mitali to make it up to
   you!

Heroku is a robust platform that empowers you to build, deploy, and scale your applications easily.

Focus on Your Code : Heroku handles the complex infrastructure so you can focus on what you do best — writing code. Scale Effortlessly : As your app grows, Heroku scales seamlessly with it. column7: OpenAI gives ChatGPT to Uncle Sam for $1
column9:

AI Snacks p*

Bite-sized AI news, fresh daily






po8 OpenAI Basically Gives ChatGPT to the Entire U.S. Government

 * OpenAI just sold ChatGPT Enterprise access to every federal agency for $1 each. That's right b the same government that spent
   $2.3 billion on a healthcare website is getting AI for the price of a gas station energy drink.

 * Why it matters: This is the ultimate loss-leader strategy. OpenAI is buying government market share and betting that once
   bureaucrats get hooked on AI-generated memos, they'll never go back to actual thinking. (source
   [https://openai.com/index/providing-chatgpt-to-the-entire-us-federal-workforce/])




p! Big on AI? Not big on spending?*

 * Galaxy.ai is the #1 AI platform with 3000+ AI tools (everythingbfrom text to video) at one place for just ($15/mo)

 * p, ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Grok, Llama, Perplexity, DeepSeek

 * p, Veo 3, Luma, Kling, Pika, HeyGen, RunwayML, Hailuo (Minimax)

 * p Works seamlessly on web, iOS, and Android

 * p	 Try Galaxy.ai now [https://galaxy.ai]

*sponsored




p Google Throws $1 Billion at Universities to Create Gemini Addicts

 * Google's dropping a cool billion over three years to get college students hooked on Gemini. Over 100 universities signed up
   faster than freshmen register for "Intro to Basket Weaving."

 * Why it matters: It's the ultimate long game b get them while they're young and broke, then charge them enterprise prices when
   they graduate into corporate jobs. (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/world/us/google-commits-1-billion-ai-training-us-universities-2025-08-06/])

B


p Britain Discovers AI Needs Electricity, Panics

 * The UK wants to be an AI superpower but just realized their electricity costs are astronomical. Turns out you can't run data
   centers on tea and good intentions.

 * Why it matters: While Silicon Valley argues about AGI timelines, Britain is learning that the real bottleneck isn't
   intelligence b it's the electric bill. (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/britains-ai-hopes-face-harsh-reality-high-electricity-costs-2025-08-07/])

B


p	 Google Gaslights Publishers About AI Killing Their Traffic

 * Google claims AI search isn't destroying website traffic, just making clicks "higher quality." That's like saying a restaurant
   has fewer customers but they're really hungry.

 * Why it matters: Google's official position is basically "trust us, bro" while publishers watch their ad revenue evaporate into
   AI-generated answer boxes. (source
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/06/google-denies-ai-search-features-are-killing-website-traffic/])

B


po8 Apollo Bets Big on AI Real Estate Because Someone Has to House the Robots

 * Private equity giant Apollo bought Stream Data Centers, betting that hyperscalers will keep needing actual buildings for their
   digital empires.

 * Why it matters: While everyone's building AI models, someone's gotta build the warehouses to store them. It's like the
   California Gold Rush, but for server farms. (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/technology/apollo-buys-stream-data-centers-bet-ai-infrastructure-boom-2025-08-06/])

B


p$ Google's AI Coding Agent 'Jules' Graduates from Beta to Disappointment

 * Google launched Jules, an AI that writes code while you sleep. It's like having an intern who works 24/7 and only occasionally
   breaks production.

 * Why it matters: The race to replace developers is heating up, though Jules still can't figure out why your CSS isn't working
   either. (source [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/06/googles-ai-coding-agent-jules-is-now-out-of-beta/])

B


p'bp+ Google and OpenAI Fight Over Who Gets to Teach Your Kids

 * Google launched "Guided Learning" in Gemini to compete with ChatGPT's "Study Mode." Both companies are desperately trying to
   convince teachers they're educational tools, not cheating machines.

 * Why it matters: The AI tutoring wars have begun b may the best hallucinator win. (source
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/06/google-takes-on-chatgpts-study-mode-with-new-guided-learning-tool-in-gemini/])

B


p&	 Duolingo's Stock Soars Because AI Actually Worked (Shocking)

 * Duolingo's stock jumped 30% after AI features drove more users to pay for premium. Turns out people will pay extra to have a
   robot judge their pronunciation.

 * Why it matters: Finally, a company that used AI to make money instead of just burning VC cash. The owl is officially smarter
   than most startups. (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/duolingo-surges-ai-led-growth-forecast-raise-boost-investor-confidence-2025-08-07/])

B


p< Thomson Reuters Proves Old Media Can AI Too

 * The legal and news giant credited AI for strong revenue growth, with AI products now representing 22% of contract value.
   Lawyers love paying for AI to do their research.

 * Why it matters: Turns out having decades of authoritative content is a pretty good moat in the AI age. Who knew? (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/markets/europe/thomson-reuters-reports-higher-second-quarter-revenue-ai-helps-drive-growth-2025-08-06/])

B


p, Truth Social Gets AI Search, Powered by Perplexity (Plot Twist)

 * Trump's social platform launched AI search using Perplexity's tech, but with carefully curated information sources. It's like
   Google, but with more flags.

 * Why it matters: This shows how AI can be weaponized to create custom reality bubbles. The future is personalized misinformation
   at scale. (source
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/07/truth-socials-ai-search-is-powered-by-perplexity-but-the-platform-can-set-limits-on-sources/])

B


p8o8 Tavily Raises $25M to Babysit AI Agents on the Internet

 * A startup that helps AI agents browse the web safely just raised $25M. Because apparently we need AI chaperones to make sure
   our robots don't embarrass us online.

 * Why it matters: As AI agents get more autonomous, someone needs to make sure they don't accidentally start international
   incidents or order 10,000 bananas. (source
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/06/tavily-raises-25m-to-connect-ai-agents-to-the-web/])

B


p EPAM Makes Bank Helping Companies Pretend They Understand AI

 * IT consulting firm EPAM raised forecasts because everyone wants AI but nobody knows how to build it. It's like the Y2K
   consulting boom, but with more buzzwords.

 * Why it matters: The real AI gold rush isn't building models b it's charging companies to figure out what to do with them.
   (source [https://www.reuters.com/technology/software-provider-epam-lifts-annual-forecasts-ai-driven-demand-2025-08-07/])

B


p Someone Wants $20/Month for an AI Browser

 * The Browser Company launched a $20/month subscription for their AI browser Dia. That's more expensive than Netflix, for the
   privilege of having AI read websites to you.

 * Why it matters: This will test whether people are willing to pay premium prices for AI features, or if they'll just stick with
   Chrome and complain about it for free. (source
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/06/the-browser-company-launches-a-20-monthly-subscription-for-its-ai-powered-browser/])

B


p Bumble's AI Makeover Can't Fix the Fact That Dating Sucks

 * Bumble lost 8.7% of paying users despite adding AI features. Turns out artificial intelligence can't solve the very real
   problem of human beings being terrible at dating.

 * Why it matters: A reminder that slapping AI on a broken product doesn't magically fix it. Sometimes the problem isn't the
   algorithm b it's the humans. (source
   [https://www.reuters.com/business/bumbles-paying-user-drop-sparks-concerns-over-pace-ai-driven-revamp-2025-08-06/])

B


p$ Amazon's New Alexa+ Is Still Dumber Than a Goldfish

 * Early tests of Amazon's AI-powered Alexa+ reveal it's still pretty bad at basic tasks like remembering numbers or not
   hallucinating your email content.

 * Why it matters: After years of hype, the "smart" home assistant is still about as reliable as asking your cat to take notes. At
   least the cat doesn't pretend to understand you. (source
   [https://techcrunch.com/2025/08/06/first-impressions-of-alexa-amazons-upgraded-ai-powered-digital-assistant/])
